# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The choice of the permanent capital of the U.S. state of Colorado was put to a popular vote in 1881.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The cities in active contention were: Denver, Del Norte, Pueblo, Colorado Springs, Canon City, and Salida.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The City of Denver, which had been the temporary capital since Colorado became a state in 1876, was chosen by 66 percent of voters.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Denver City was always the largest town in the Territory of Colorado since its recognition in 1861, and then the state, admitted to the union in 1876, there were always those in the state who opposed putting the capital in Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The first meeting of the Colorado territorial legislature, held in Denver in 1861, chose Colorado City (now part of Colorado Springs) as the capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] But when the legislature met in Colorado City for the first time in 1862, the facilities were so inadequate that after five days, the delegates voted to adjourn and reconvene in Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] But when they reconvened in Denver, they chose not to stay there, and named Golden as the territorial capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Golden was officially the territorial capital, the legislature often met in Denver, because it was more of a city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In 1867, the legislature voted to move the state government to Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Denver had enough influence to prevent the removal of the acting capital from Denver, there was also enough opposition to prevent it from being designated as the permanent capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] When Colorado drafted a constitution for admission as a state in 1876, the framers feared that if the state constitution designated any city as the permanent state capital, it would arouse enough opposition that the voters would not ratify the constitution.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] To solve the dilemma, the Colorado state constitution kicked the problem down the road by providing that a permanent state capital would be chosen by statewide popular vote five years later, in 1881.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Although Denver was a transportation hub, and had more than twice the population of the next-largest city in Colorado, four other cities put themselves forward as sites for the capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver's rivals hoped to use antipathy toward Denver to have themselves named as the capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Some of the larger towns in Colorado did not mount active campaigns for the capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Leadville, which in 1880 census was the second-most populous town in Colorado with a population of 14,820, showed no interest in becoming state capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Neither did Silver Cliff, then Colorado's third-largest with a population of 5,040.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Golden, which had hosted the territorial government from 1862 to 1867, did not try to win back the capital in 1881.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver had grown considerably since it became the temporary territorial capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The growth had been considerably aided by the establishment of a railroad connection in 1870, from Denver eastward, by the Kansas Pacific Railroad.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] This early rail connection made Denver the hub for movement of people and supplies to and from other points in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver was far larger than any of its rivals for state capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver had enjoyed the economic stimulus of hosting the state government, and was eager to make it permanent.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It had the advantage of being by far the largest town in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Committees were formed to visit other parts of the state promoting Denver as the capital, and assuring other cities that Denver wanted only the capital, and in return, Denver would support the location of other institutions, such as the university and the school of mines, outside of Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Businessman Henry Brown offered to donate ten acres near downtown Denver for a new state capitol building, if Denver were chosen to have it.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver supporters hailed the offer, and noted that the tract as an ideal spot, with a grand westward vista toward the mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Detractors noted that Brown owned more real estate in the vicinity, which would jump in value if the state capitol building were to be nearby.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Colorado Springs was at the time the fourth most-populous town in Colorado, with 4,226 inhabitants.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Founded in 1871, it was growing rapidly, and touted its more genteel atmosphere compared to Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Supporters noted that most older states had wisely located their capitals away from large commercial cities.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In 1880, Pueblo had 3,217 inhabitants, not large enough to put it in the top five most populous towns in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] But Pueblo had once come close to becoming the territorial capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In 1874, the Colorado territorial house had passed a bill to make Pueblo the capital, but the measure was not passed by the territorial senate.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The *Pueblo Chieftain* maintained that Pueblo was the most pleasant city to place the capital, and had plenty of good hotels and restaurants to satisfy the legislators.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Canon City had a population of 1,501 in the 1880 census.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It was principally a supply point on the Arkansas River for the mines and oil field.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It promoted itself as having the most pleasant climate in the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] It was awarded the territorial prison after losing the contest for the Colorado state capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Salida had been founded just the preceding year, and had missed the 1880 census.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The campaign for state capital consisted of editorials in Salida's weekly newspaper, the *Mountain Mail*.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The *Mail* printed a distorted map of Colorado showing Salida in the exact geographical center.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The referendum was held on 8 November 1881.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In each city vying for state capital, lopsided majorities voted for their hometowns.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] In Pueblo County, 2,039 voted for Pueblo, and just 44 for other towns.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Arapahoe County, of which Denver was then the county seat, held off releasing its count until nearly all of the other counties had reported, counted 8,839 votes for Denver, which were 99.8 percent of the 8,857 ballots counted.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver won on the first ballot, thus avoiding a runoff vote.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Denver was widely accused of buying votes, and bribing newspaper editors to back it for the state capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The editor of the Salida *Mountain Mail* congratulated Denver on its victory, and noted that Denver was a beautiful city that deserved the capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The editor confessed that the campaign for Salida was just a publicity stunt to bring the town to public attention, and that it had succeeded.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] He wrote that although Denver had spent "thousands of dollars, perhaps hundreds of thousands" bribing newspaper editors and hiring "bummers" to vote for Denver, the money had performed a public service by supporting newspapers and indigent citizens across the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Since 1881, local myths have grown that various other towns in Colorado were in serious contention to become state capital, among them: Central City, Cripple Creek, Fountain, Golden, Laporte, Leadville, and Silver Cliff.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] The town of Cripple Creek was not even in existence until 1892, eleven years after the referendum.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum] Webpages about Central City, Laporte, and Silver Cliff have claimed that not only were those towns in serious contention to be the state capital, but that each town lost the referendum to Denver by a single vote.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Of the 37 states admitted to the Union by Congress, all but six have been established within existing U.S. organized incorporated territories.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] A state that was so created might encompass all or part of a territory.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The use of an enabling act has been a common historic practice, but several states were admitted to the Union without one.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] In many instances, an enabling act would detail the mechanism by which the territory would be admitted as a state after the ratification of their constitution and the election of state officers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Although the use of such an act is a traditional historic practice, several territories have drafted constitutions for submission to Congress absent an enabling act but were subsequently admitted.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The broad outline for the process was established by the Land Ordinance of 1784 and the 1787 Northwest Ordinance, both of which predate the U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The Admission to the Union Clause forbids the creation of new states from parts of existing states without the consent of all of the affected states and that of Congress.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The primary intent of the caveat was to give the four Eastern States that still had western land claims (Connecticut, Georgia, North Carolina, and Virginia) a veto over whether their western counties could become states.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The clause has since served the same function each time that a proposal to partition an existing state or states has arisen.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Between 1781 and 1789, the United States was governed by a unicameral Congress, the Congress of the Confederation, which operated under authority granted to it by the Articles of Confederation, the nation's first constitution.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The 11th Article authorized Congress to admit new states to the Union provided nine states consented.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Under the Articles, each state cast one vote on each proposed measure in Congress.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] During this period, the Confederation Congress enacted two ordinances governing the admission of new states into the Union.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The first such ordinance was the Land Ordinance of 1784, enacted April 23, 1784.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Thomas Jefferson was its principal author.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The ordinance called for the land (recently confirmed as part of the United States by the Treaty of Paris) west of the Appalachian Mountains, north of the Ohio River and east of the Mississippi River to eventually be divided into ten states.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Once a given area reached 20,000 inhabitants, it could call a constitutional convention and form a provisional government.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Then, upon enacting a state constitution which affirmed that the new state would forever be part of the Confederation, it would be admitted on an equal footing with all other states, based on a majority vote in Congress.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The 1784 ordinance was superseded three years later by the Northwest Ordinance of 1787.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Enacted by the Confederation Congress on July 13, 1787, it created the Northwest Territory, the first organized incorporated territory of the United States.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] No new states were formed in the Northwest Territory under either ordinance.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] In 1789, the 1st United States Congress reaffirmed the Northwest Ordinance with slight modifications.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The Northwest Territory remained in existence until 1803, when the southeastern portion of it was admitted to the Union as the State of Ohio, and the remainder was reorganized.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] At the 1787 Constitutional Convention, a proposal to include the phrase "new States shall be admitted on the same terms with the original States" in the *new states* clause was defeated.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] That proposal would have taken the policy articulated in the Ordinance of 1784 and made it a constitutional imperative.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Many delegates objected to including the phrase, fearing that the political power of future new western states would ultimately overwhelm that of the established eastern states.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Delegates, understanding that the number of states would inevitably increase, did agree to include wording into this clause to preclude formation of a new state out of an established one without the consent of the established state as well as the Congress.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] It was anticipated that Kentucky (which was a part of Virginia), Franklin (which was a part of North Carolina, and later became part of the Southwest Territory), Vermont (to which New York asserted a disputed claim), and Maine (which was a part of Massachusetts), would become states.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] As a result of this compromise, new breakaway states are permitted to join the Union but only with the proper consents.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Shortly after the new Constitution went into effect Congress admitted Vermont and Kentucky on equal terms with the existing 13 states and thereafter formalized the condition in its acts of admission for subsequent states.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Thus the Congress, utilizing the discretion allowed by the framers, adopted a policy of equal status for all newly admitted states.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The constitutional principle derived from these actions is known as the equal footing doctrine.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] With the growth of states' rights advocacy during the antebellum period, the Supreme Court asserted, in *Lessee of Pollard v.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Hagan* (1845), that the Constitution mandated admission of new states on the basis of equality.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Historically, most new states formed by Congress have been established from an organized incorporated U.S. territory, created and governed by Congress in accord with its plenary power under Article IV, Section 3, Clause 2 of the Constitution.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] In some cases, an entire territory became a state; in others some part of a territory became a state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] In most cases, the organized government of a territory made known the sentiment of its population in favor of statehood, usually by referendum.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Congress then empowered that government to organize a constitutional convention to write a state constitution.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Upon acceptance of that constitution, by the people of the territory and then by Congress, Congress would adopt by simple majority vote a joint resolution granting statehood.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Then the President of the United States would sign the resolution and issue a proclamation announcing that a new state had been added to the Union.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] While Congress, which has ultimate authority over the admission of new states, has usually followed this procedure, there have been occasions when it did not.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Congress is under no obligation to admit states, even in those areas whose population expresses a desire for statehood.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] In one instance, Mormon pioneers in Salt Lake City sought to establish the state of Deseret in 1849.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] It existed for slightly over two years and was never approved by the Congress.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] In 1905, leaders of the Five Civilized Tribes (Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Seminole) in Indian Territory proposed to establish the state of Sequoyah as a means to retain control of their lands.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The proposed constitution ultimately failed in Congress.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Instead, the Indian Territory was incorporated into the new state of Oklahoma in 1907.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Some U.S. territories existed only a short time before becoming states, while others remained territories for decades.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The shortest-lived was Alabama Territory at 2 years, while New Mexico and Hawaii territories both were in existence for more than 50 years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The entry of several states into the Union has been delayed by complicating factors.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Among them, Michigan Territory, which petitioned Congress for statehood in 1835, was not admitted to the Union until 1837, because of a boundary dispute with the adjacent state of Ohio.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] The independent Republic of Texas requested annexation to the United States in 1837, but fears about potential conflict with Mexico delayed the admission of Texas for nine years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Also, statehood for Kansas Territory was held up for several years (1854–1861) because of a series of internal violent conflicts involving anti-slavery and pro-slavery factions.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] Once established, most state borders have, with few exceptions, been generally stable.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] There have been numerous minor adjustments to state boundaries over the years as a result of improved surveys, resolution of ambiguous or disputed boundary definitions, or minor mutually agreed boundary adjustments for administrative convenience or other purposes.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] One notable example is the case *New Jersey v.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/admission-to-the-union] New York*, in which New Jersey won roughly 90% of Ellis Island from New York in 1998.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] On August 25, 1855, the Kansas Territorial Legislature created a huge Arapahoe County to govern the entire western portion of the Territory of Kansas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The county was named for the Arapaho Nation, who lived in the region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] In July 1858, gold was discovered along the South Platte River in Arapahoe County (in present-day Englewood).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] This discovery precipitated the Pike's Peak Gold Rush.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Many residents of the mining region felt disconnected from the remote territorial governments of Kansas and Nebraska, so they voted to form their own Territory of Jefferson on October 24, 1859.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The following month, the Jefferson Territorial Legislature organized 12 counties for the new territory, including a smaller Arapahoe County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Denver City served as the county seat of Arapahoe County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The Jefferson Territory never received federal sanction, and when the State of Kansas was admitted to the Union on January 29, 1861, the mining regions temporarily reverted to unorganized territory.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] On February 28, 1861, Congress passed an act organizing the Territory of Colorado, using present-day borders.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] On November 1, 1861, the Colorado Territorial Assembly organized the 17 original counties of Colorado, including a new Arapahoe County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County originally stretched from the line of present-day Sheridan Boulevard 160 miles (260 km) east to the Kansas border, and from the line of present-day County Line Road 30 miles (48 km) north to the 40th parallel north (168th Avenue).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Denver City served as the county seat of Arapahoe County until 1902.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] In 1901, the Colorado General Assembly voted to split Arapahoe County into three parts — a new consolidated City and County of Denver, a new Adams County, and the remainder of the Arapahoe County to be renamed South Arapahoe County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] A ruling by the Colorado Supreme Court, subsequent legislation, and a referendum delayed the reorganization until November 15, 1902.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Governor James Bradley Orman designated Littleton as the temporary county seat of South Arapahoe County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] On April 11, 1903, the Colorado General Assembly changed the name of South Arapahoe County back to Arapahoe County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] On November 8, 1904, Arapahoe County voters chose Littleton over Englewood by a vote of 1310 to 829 to be the permanent county seat.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Census Bureau, the county has a total area of 805 square miles (2,080 km2), of which 798 square miles (2,070 km2) are land and 7.3 square miles (19 km2) (0.9%) are covered by water.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The county measures 72 mi (116 km) east-west and 4 to 12 mi (6.4 to 19.3 km) north-south.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Two exclaves of Arapahoe County are entirely surrounded by the City and County of Denver, the City of Glendale, and the Holly Hills neighborhood, a census-designated place.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 655,070.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Of the residents, 23.4% were under the age of 18 and 13.8% were 65 years of age or older; the median age was 36.6 years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] For every 100 females there were 98.6 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 96.6 males.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] 97.9% of residents lived in urban areas and 2.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 60.5% White, 10.8% Black or African American, 1.0% American Indian and Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 0.3% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 8.3% from some other race, and 12.6% from two or more races.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 20.7% of the population.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] There were 250,206 households in the county, of which 32.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 26.0% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] About 26.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] There were 262,493 housing units, of which 4.7% were vacant.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Among occupied housing units, 62.5% were owner-occupied and 37.5% were renter-occupied.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.9% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.3%.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] As of the census of 2000, 487,967 people, 190,909 households, and 125,809 families were residing in the county.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The population density was 608 people/mi2 (235 people/km2).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The 196,835 housing units averaged 245 per square mile (95/km2).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The racial makeup of the county was 79.93% White, 7.67% African American, 0.66% Native American, 3.95% Asian, 0.12% Pacific Islander, 4.51% from other races, and 3.16% from two or more races.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Hispanics or Latinos of any race made up 11.81% of the population.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Of the 190,909 households, 34.90% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 51.20% were married couples living together, 10.60% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.10% were not families.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] About 27.00% of all households were made up of individuals, and 5.90% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The average household size was 2.53, and the average family size was 3.11.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 97.10 males.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.20 males.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The median income for a household was $53,570, and for a family was $63,875.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Males had a median income of $41,601 versus $31,612 for females.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The per capita income for the county was $28,147.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] About 4.20% of families and 5.80% of the population were below the poverty line, including 7.00% of those under age 18 and 5.10% of those age 65 or over.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County is home to nine public school districts: Aurora, Bennett, Byers, Cherry Creek, Deer Trail, Englewood, Littleton, Sheridan, and Strasburg.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] There are also several private schools throughout the county, including St.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Mary's Academy in Cherry Hills Village, Regis Jesuit High School in Aurora, and Kent Denver School in Englewood.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County is home to two large community colleges: Arapahoe Community College in Littleton, and the Community College of Aurora.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The county is also home to the University of Colorado Anschutz Medical Campus and the Denver South campus of Colorado Technical University, both located in Aurora.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Arapahoe County was once a classic bastion of suburban conservatism.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] In the 1924 Colorado gubernatorial election, Republican Clarence Morley, who was openly affiliated with the Ku Klux Klan, won over 66% of the vote in Arapahoe County, a higher percentage than he received in any other county in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] In addition, the county for many years was represented in congress by Republican Tom Tancredo, a hardcore conservative known for his controversial anti-immigration, anti-Catholic, and nativist political beliefs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] As the Denver Metro Area grew in the 1960s and beyond, Arapahoe County became the most Republican county in the state outside of Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] However, heavy urbanization, demographic changes and population increases - such as the rapid diversification of Aurora's population and younger professionals in the southern suburbs - have caused the county to become much more competitive since the 1990s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] It swung from a 22-point win for George H.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Bush in 1988 to only a three-point win in 1992.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] By the turn of the millennium, it had become more of a suburban swing county.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] In 2008, the county swung over dramatically to support Barack Obama, who became the first Democrat to carry it since 1964, and only the second since 1936.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] It swung from a four-point win for George W.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] Bush in 2004 to a 13-point win for Obama in 2008.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] In the 2020 election, Joe Biden turned in the strongest showing for a Democrat in over a century, becoming the first Democrat to win over 60% of the vote since 1916.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The bulk of the population and political strength of Arapahoe County is located in Colorado's 6th congressional district, Tancredo's former district, centered in Aurora and represented by Jason Crow.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/arapahoe-county-colorado] The more rural eastern parts of the county are located in the 4th District represented by Lauren Boebert while the Denver enclave portions such as Glendale and Holly Hills are in the Denver-based 1st District represented by Diana DeGette.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City, Kansas Territory, was laid out on January 17, 1858, during the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, but then the land was left idle.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] A new company "jumped the claim" to the town's site in late 1859, and it put up the first building in February 1860.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The Cañon City, Kansas Territory, post office opened on December 13, 1860.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The spelling of the town's name frequently omitted the tilde over the Spanish letter ñ.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] This town was originally intended as a commercial center for mining in South Park and the upper Arkansas River.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The new Territory of Colorado was organized on February 28, 1861, and Fremont County, Colorado Territory was created on November 1, 1861, with Cañon City as the first and only county seat.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] In 1861, the town raised two companies of volunteers to serve with the Second Colorado Infantry during the American Civil War.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] This regiment fought in skirmishes in nearby New Mexico and as far east as the Indian Territory (Oklahoma) and Missouri before ending its organization in 1865.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cassaday drilled for petroleum 6 miles (10 km) north of Cañon City, close to a known oil seep.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cassaday struck oil at the depth of 50 feet (15 m), and he completed the first commercial oil well west of the Mississippi River.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] He drilled five or six more wells nearby, and he refined kerosene and fuel oil from the petroleum.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Congress approved the Territory of Colorado's request for funds to construct a penitentiary in 1867.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The Colorado Territorial Penitentiary opened in 1871, becoming Colorado's first prison.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The original structure held 43 prisoners, though the number of incarcerated people increased steadily to over 400 people by the turn of the century.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Records of inmate labor at the penitentiary date to 1872, including numerous complaints that inmates were not receiving full compensation for their work.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Incarcerated workers contributed significantly to the development of the city, including the construction of Skyline Drive by 60 inmates.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The City of Cañon City was incorporated on April 3, 1872.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] A number of metal ore smelters were built in Cañon City following the discovery of gold at Cripple Creek in 1891.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] On July 30, 1904, the spelling of the Cañon City post office was changed to the common English spelling "Canyon City", but the spelling was changed back to the Spanish spelling "Cañon City" on December 15 of that year.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The Cañon City Downtown Historic District is an historic district that was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1983.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City is located in eastern Fremont County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] It sits primarily on the north side of the Arkansas River, just east of where the river exits from Royal Gorge.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] It is bordered to the south by the unincorporated community of Lincoln Park.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Route 50, Pueblo is 39 miles (63 km) to the east and Poncha Springs is 62 miles (100 km) to the west.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Colorado Springs is 45 miles (72 km) to the northeast.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] At the 2020 United States census, the city had a total area of 7,939 acres (32.127 km2) including 7.9 acres (0.032 km2) of water.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The city's nickname, "the Climate Capital of Colorado", derives from the combination of unique geography and 5,300-foot (1,600 m) elevation protecting the city from harsh weather conditions.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The average daily high temperature in January is 14 °F (7.8 °C) warmer in Cañon City than in Grand Junction, even though the elevation of Cañon City is higher.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The average minimum temperature in January is 20 °F (−7 °C).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] During July, overnight lows are 59 °F (15 °C) on average.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City has a semi-arid climate (Köppen climate classification **BSk**).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] As Cañon City has grown, the city has both annexed surrounding communities and developed new subdivisions to create the city that exists today.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City is home to many city-owned parks, as well as parks owned by the Cañon City Area Recreation and Park District.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The Cañon City Area Recreation and Park District, commonly called the Rec District, was created in 1965 to better serve the community's recreational needs with parks, the R.C.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Icabone Pool (a public swimming pool), a dog park, an archery range and a ropes course along with a rec district office with a community room.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] In addition, the city maintains the Tunnel Drive Trail, a four-mile long out-and-back trail that follows the course of an old irrigation canal.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The trailhead is located at the west end of Tunnel Drive, just inside the city limits.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Hardy Award for Service to Outdoor Recreation was created in the name of Guy U.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Hardy to recognize people in the community who "help preserve, protect and advocate for providing outdoor recreation opportunities." Hardy had a significant impact on outdoor recreational opportunities in the Royal Gorge area.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] As of the 2020 census, Cañon City had a population of 17,141.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] 19.0% of residents were under the age of 18 and 25.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] For every 100 females there were 102.4 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 102.1 males age 18 and over.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] 98.1% of residents lived in urban areas, while 1.9% lived in rural areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] There were 7,107 households in Cañon City, of which 23.7% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Of all households, 42.3% were married-couple households, 19.7% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 31.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] About 35.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 19.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] There were 7,631 housing units, of which 6.9% were vacant.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.9% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.9%.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Along with a police department, sheriff's office and detention center, and a municipal court, Cañon City is home to the courts for Fremont County and the 11th Judicial District of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] It has been described as "America’s cheeriest prison town".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City is governed via the Council–manager government system.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The city council consists of seven members who are elected from districts.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The mayor is elected by the entire city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The area being situated along the Arkansas River has allowed for soil suitable to orchards, ranching, and farming, but has largely grown to rely on the large number of state and federal prisons in the area, as well as to tourism, education, manufacturing, medicine and many other sectors.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City depends on the Colorado Department of Corrections and federal prison system, and its tourism industry which includes the Royal Gorge Route Railroad, Royal Gorge Bridge and Park, Red Canyon Park, The Abbey winery, and various other attractions.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The major local employers include downtown shops, the entrepreneurial TechSTART initiative that attracts major technology-based entrepreneurs, and CommonSpirit (owner of St.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Thomas More Hospital and the Progressive Care Center).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Prisons have served an important significance to both Cañon City and the surrounding areas of Fremont County, as well as to the state of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The Museum of Colorado Prisons has been given the role of preserving and presenting the past of the state's corrections system.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Colorado Department of Corrections operates the Colorado Territorial Correctional Facility in Cañon City.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] In addition to several correctional facilities near Cañon City in unincorporated areas in Fremont County, Colorado State Penitentiary, the location of the state death row and execution chamber is in Fremont County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Other state prisons in Fremont County include Arrowhead Correctional Center, Centennial Correctional Facility, Fremont Correctional Facility, Four Mile Correctional Center, ADX Florence, and Skyline Correctional Center.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] On October 3, 1929, a riot at the prison claimed 13 lives.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The Colorado Women's Correctional Facility near Cañon City in unincorporated Fremont County was decommissioned on June 4, 2009.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] From Cañon City's Downtown Historic District located in the heart of the city to the Royal Gorge Bridge, there are many places to see and visit in the area.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City is home to a daily newspaper, called the *Cañon City Daily Record*; an FM radio station, Star Country 104.5 FM; and a long-running AM radio station, known as KRLN NewsRadio 1400 AM.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Transportation in the Cañon City area consists of cab service, shuttle bus service, and a downtown wagon ride.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The Royal Gorge Bridge trolley had also been used during special events (it was destroyed in the Royal Gorge Fire, but it was reserved for use by the Royal Gorge Bridge & Park.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Jeep tours and Segway tours are also available to explore local parks such as Red Canyon Park or scenic places such as Skyline Drive.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The town is served by the Fremont County airport (1V6) which is 6 miles to the East and currently has no scheduled passenger service.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Within an hour's drive is the Colorado Springs Airport with daily service by major airlines.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The area is served by one state and one U.S. highway with a mix of city and county roads to navigate the city or connect to neighboring areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City's school system is under the direction of the Cañon City School District Fremont RE-1.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The district currently has four elementary schools, one charter school, one school serving as both an elementary school and middle school, one middle school and one high school, Cañon City High School.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City's higher education needs are served by the Pueblo Community College Fremont Campus, located on the west end of the city along U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The movie *Canon City* (1948) depicts the real-life 1947 escape of 12 prisoners from nearby Colorado State Penitentiary.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City, Colorado is referenced as the location of the fourth stage of the Steel Ball Run race, in the seventh part of JoJo's Bizarre Adventure.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] The stage begins in Cañon City in Chapter 32 of the series.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] A diner in Cañon City is the setting of the song "Navajo Rug", which was named by the Western Writers of America as one of the Top 100 Western Songs of all time.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] A fictional version of the city is depicted in Philip K.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Dick's alternate history novel *The Man in the High Castle* (1962) and its eponymous 2015 television series adaptation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/canon-city-colorado] Cañon City is in an ostensibly-demilitarized "neutral zone" between the puppet regimes of the Japanese Pacific States, in the west, and Greater Nazi Reich, in the east, in the former United States.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] On May 6, 1859, during the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, John H.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Gregory found a gold-bearing vein (the Gregory Lode) in Gregory Gulch between Black Hawk and Central City.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Within two months many other veins were discovered, including the Bates, Gunnell, Kansas, and Burroughs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The Mountain City, Kansas Territory, post office opened on January 17, 1860 The area uphill (west) from Mountain City was known as Central City.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] As many as 10,000 prospectors soon flocked to the town and surrounding prospects.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] President James Buchanan signed an act creating the free Territory of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] On November 1, 1861, the Colorado Territory created Gilpin County with Central City as the county seat.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The year 1863 brought the first attempt by hard rock miners to form a hard rock miners' union.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Of 125 miners signing a union resolution in Mountain City, about fifty broke windows and doors at the Bob Tail mine, forcing other workers out.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] After a night of shooting and fighting, the union effort among Central City miners failed.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] On March 11, 1864, Mountain City, Colorado Territory, was officially incorporated, with John S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Many Chinese immigrants lived in Mountain City during the early days working the placer deposits of Gregory Gulch.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] They were forbidden to work in the underground mines.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Most of them are believed to have returned to China after making their stake.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The frontier gambler Poker Alice lived for a time in Central City and several other Colorado mining communities.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] As the mining pits expanded, the Mountain City post office was moved uphill and reopened as the Central City, Colorado Territory, post office on October 8, 1869.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] On April 28, 1873, the city was visited by U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Grant and the first lady, who arrived with a group including Governor Elbert, ex-governor Edward M.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Teller, General Harney, and General Babcock.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The party came to Black Hawk from Golden via train, then transferred to carriages for the transit to Central City.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Upon arrival, the procession paraded through town, which was thronged with spectators, before stopping at the Teller House at 1 p.m.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] In preparation for their visit, the sidewalk leading to the entrance had been covered with silver bricks from the Caribou Mine, valued at about $13,000.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] President Grant was reportedly incredulous when he walked over the silver bricks to the entrance and learned that they were pure silver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] After dinner and a reception, the party departed for Idaho Springs, the next stop on Grant's tour of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] On May 22, 1874, a fire started in a Chinese laundry on Gregory street at 11 a.m. and spread quickly throughout the town.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] A request for help was sent to Golden and the Excelsior Fire Company took a special train to Central City to help fight the fire, arriving to cheers from the locals.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Smoke billowing from the fire could be observed as far as Denver, which also sent a fire engine by train after receiving a dispatch to the mayor of Denver stating "The flames are still raging.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Send assistance." By 3:30 p.m. the fire was under control, but not before destroying most of the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The Teller House, Catholic church, Roworth's City Bakery, and several other structures survived the fire, while about 150 structures were destroyed.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Many people lost their homes, businesses and belongings as a result, forcing the town to undertake a large effort to rebuild.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Total losses from the fire were estimated to exceed half a million dollars.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] To help prevent future fires, ordinances were passed to widen the city streets and build a water supply for fire prevention.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Gold mining in the Central City district decreased rapidly between 1900 and 1920, as the veins were exhausted.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Mining revived in the early 1930s in response to the increase in the price of gold from $20 to $35 per ounce, but then virtually shut down during World War II when gold mining was declared nonessential to the war effort.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The district was enlivened in the 1950s by efforts to locate uranium deposits, but these proved unsuccessful.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The City of Central was reincorporated on June 12, 1886.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The population of Central City and its sister city Black Hawk fell to a few hundred by the 1950s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Casino gambling was introduced in both towns in the early 1990s, but had more success in Black Hawk (which has 18 casinos) than in Central City (which has 6 casinos), partly because the main road to Central City passed through Black Hawk, tempting gamblers to stop in Black Hawk instead.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] In an effort to compete, Central City completed a four-lane, 8.4-mile (13.5 km) parkway from Interstate 70 to Central City, without going through Black Hawk.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The highway was completed in 2004, but Black Hawk, which prior to the introduction of gambling was much smaller than Central City, continues to generate more than seven times the gambling revenue that Central City does.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] To compete, Central City has recently eliminated height restrictions for building on undeveloped land.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Buildings were previously limited to heights of 53 feet (16 m), so as not to overshadow the town's historic buildings.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Tax from the gambling revenue provides funding for the State Historical Fund, administered by the Colorado Office of Archaeology and Historic Preservation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Central City is located in southern Gilpin County.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The city limits extend south along the Central City Parkway into Clear Creek County, as far as Interstate 70.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The city is bordered by Black Hawk to the east and Idaho Springs to the south.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] At the 2020 United States census, the city had a total area of 1,382 acres (5.5940 km2), including 0.07 acres (0.0003 km2) of water.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] As of the census of 2000, there were 515 people, 261 households, and 101 families residing in the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The population density was 273.0 inhabitants per square mile (105.4/km2).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] There were 394 housing units at an average density of 208.8 per square mile (80.6/km2).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The racial makeup of the city was 91.84% White, 0.19% Black or African American, 1.55% Native American, 1.17% Asian, 1.17% Pacific Islander, 2.52% from other races, and 1.55% from two or more races.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] 9.32% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] There were 261 households, out of which 17.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 26.8% were married couples living together, 8.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 61.3% were non-families.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] 43.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 6.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The average household size was 1.97 and the average family size was 2.76.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] In the city, the population was spread out, with 16.5% under the age of 18, 10.1% from 18 to 24, 34.0% from 25 to 44, 30.9% from 45 to 64, and 8.5% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] For every 100 females, there were 115.5 males.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 115.0 males.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The median income for a household in the city was $30,921, and the median income for a family was $31,667.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Males had a median income of $32,917 versus $25,446 for females.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The per capita income for the city was $26,465.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] About 7.4% of families and 12.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 8.3% of those under age 18 and 5.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Central City Public Schools are part of the Gilpin County School District RE-1.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The district has one elementary school and one high school, Gilpin County Elementary School and Gilpin County Undivided High School.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] The Black Hawk & Central City Tramway, operated by the cities of Black Hawk and Central City, provides a free shuttle between the two towns.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/central-city-colorado] Ramblin Express and Ace Express Coaches provides transportation from Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The region has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly much longer.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains was a major migration route for early peoples who spread throughout the Americas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1848, much of the Nuevo México region was annexed to the United States with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Pike's Peak Gold Rush of 1858–1862 created an influx of settlers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On February 28, 1861, U.S. president James Buchanan signed an act creating the Territory of Colorado, and on August 1, 1876, president Ulysses S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Grant signed Proclamation 230, admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Denver is the capital, the most populous city, and the center of the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado Springs is the second-most populous city of the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Residents of the state are known as Coloradans, although the antiquated "Coloradoan" is occasionally used.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado generally ranks as one of the top U.S. states for education attainment, employment, and healthcare quality.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Major parts of its economy include government and defense, mining, agriculture, tourism, and manufacturing.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] With increasing temperatures and decreasing water availability, Colorado's agriculture, forestry, and tourism economies are expected to be heavily affected by climate change.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The region that is today the State of Colorado has been inhabited by Native Americans and their Paleo-Indian ancestors for at least 13,500 years and possibly more than 37,000 years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Lindenmeier site contains artifacts dating from approximately 8720 BCE.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Ancient Pueblo peoples lived in the valleys and mesas of the Colorado Plateau in far southwestern Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Ute Nation inhabited the mountain valleys of the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Western Rocky Mountains, even as far east as the Front Range of the present day.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Apache and the Comanche also inhabited the Eastern and Southeastern parts of the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In the 17th century, the Arapaho and Cheyenne moved west from the Great Lakes region to hunt across the High Plains of Colorado and Wyoming.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The U.S. acquired the territorial claim to the eastern Rocky Mountains with the Louisiana Purchase from France in 1803.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Army reconnaissance expedition into the disputed region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colonel Pike and his troops were arrested by Spanish cavalrymen in the San Luis Valley the following February, taken to Chihuahua, and expelled from Mexico the following July.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Under the 1819 Adams-Onís Treaty, the U.S. acquired Florida from Spain while relinquishing claims to lands west of the 100th meridian and south of both the Arkansas River and the 42nd parallel.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The treaty took effect on February 22, 1821.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Having settled its border with Spain, the U.S. admitted the southeastern portion of the Territory of Missouri to the Union as the state of Missouri on August 10, 1821.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The remainder of Missouri Territory, including what would become northeastern Colorado, became an unorganized territory and remained so for 33 years over the question of slavery.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] After 11 years of war, Spain finally recognized the independence of Mexico with the Treaty of Córdoba signed on August 24, 1821.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Mexico eventually ratified the Adams–Onís Treaty in 1831.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Texian Revolt of 1835–36 fomented a dispute between the U.S. and Mexico which eventually erupted into the Mexican–American War in 1846.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Mexico surrendered its northern territory to the U.S. with the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo after the war in 1848; this included much of the western and southern areas of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Santa Fe Trail connected the Missouri River to Santa Fe, New Mexico, where it linked with the Camino Real de Tierra Adentro extending southward into Mexico.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Others traveling overland avoided the rugged Southern Rocky Mountains, and instead followed the North Platte River and Sweetwater River to South Pass (Wyoming), the lowest crossing of the Continental Divide between the Southern Rocky Mountains and the Central Rocky Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1849, the Mormons of the Salt Lake Valley organized the extralegal State of Deseret, claiming the entire Great Basin and all lands drained by the rivers Green, Grand, and Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The federal government of the U.S. flatly refused to recognize the new Mormon government because it was theocratic and sanctioned plural marriage.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Instead, the Compromise of 1850 divided the Mexican Cession and the northwestern claims of Texas into a new state and two new territories, the state of California, the Territory of New Mexico, and the Territory of Utah.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Provisional Government of the Territory of Jefferson was an extralegal and unrecognized United States territory that existed in the Pike's Peak mining region from October 24, 1859, until it yielded to the new Territory of Colorado on June 6, 1861.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Jefferson Territory included all of the present State of Colorado and portions of the present states of Kansas, Nebraska, Utah, and Wyoming.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The people were desirous of a closer government than those five territories provided.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The government of the Jefferson Territory, while democratically elected, was never legally recognized by the United States government, although it managed the territory with relatively free rein for 19 months.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Many of the laws enacted by the General Assembly of the Territory of Jefferson were reenacted and given official sanction by the new Colorado General Assembly in 1861.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Territory of Colorado was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from February 28, 1861, until August 1, 1876, when it was admitted to the Union as the 38th State of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The territory was created during the onset of the American Civil War in the wake of the Pike's Peak Gold Rush, which brought the first large concentration of settlers from the east to the region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The war stifled growth, but following the war mining grew more industrialized and fueled the economy.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The construction of railroads further improved the economy.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The boundaries of the newly designated Colorado Territory were very similar to those of the modern State of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1861 following the beginning of the American Civil War, there were several small disputes and skirmishes between confederate supporters and union supporters.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In August, Governor Gilpin organized the 1st Colorado Infantry.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Slough led the group to New Mexico Territory in February–March 1862.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] There they fought in the battles of Apache Canyon, Glorieta Pass and Peralta.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Slough resigned in April 1862 and was replaced by Major John M.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] With resources tied up in the war there was little left over for mines, farms, and infrastructure, and Denver stagnated.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On March 26, 1862 John Evans was appointed by Abraham Lincoln as the second governor of the territory.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] He prompted investment in Denver rail projects, and founded the University of Denver in 1864.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Anti-native sentiment grew during the Civil War years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Exterminationist ideology, led in Colorado by Evans and Chivington, advocated for the total eradication of all native people in the territory.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado War worsened relations with natives until 1864 when Chivington ordered the Sand Creek Massacre and Evans was forced to resign the following spring.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1867, the Union Pacific Railroad laid its tracks west to Weir, now Julesburg, in the northeast corner of the Territory.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Union Pacific linked up with the Central Pacific Railroad at Promontory Summit, Utah, on May 10, 1869, to form the First transcontinental railroad.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Denver Pacific Railway reached Denver in June of the following year, and the Kansas Pacific arrived two months later to forge the second line across the continent.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The United States Congress passed an enabling act on March 3, 1875, specifying the requirements for the Territory of Colorado to become a state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On August 1, 1876 (four weeks after the Centennial of the United States), U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Grant signed a proclamation admitting Colorado to the Union as the 38th state and earning it the moniker "Centennial State".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The discovery of a major silver lode near Leadville in 1878 triggered the Colorado Silver Boom.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Sherman Silver Purchase Act of 1890 invigorated silver mining, and Colorado's last, but greatest, gold strike at Cripple Creek a few months later lured a new generation of gold seekers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado women were granted the right to vote on November 7, 1893, making Colorado the second state to grant universal suffrage and the first one by a popular vote (of Colorado men).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The repeal of the Sherman Silver Purchase Act in 1893 led to a staggering collapse of the mining and agricultural economy of Colorado, but the state slowly and steadily recovered.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Between the 1880s and 1930s, Denver's floriculture industry developed into a major industry in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] This period became known locally as the Carnation Gold Rush.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Both the 1913–1914 Coalfield War and the Denver streetcar strike of 1920 resulted in federal troops intervening to end the violence.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1927, the 1927-28 Colorado coal strike occurred and was ultimately successful in winning a dollar a day increase in wages.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] During it however the Columbine Mine massacre resulted in six dead strikers following a confrontation with Colorado Rangers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In a separate incident in Trinidad the mayor was accused of deputizing members of the KKK against the striking workers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] More than 5,000 Colorado miners—many immigrants—are estimated to have died in accidents since records were first formally collected following an 1884 accident in Crested Butte that killed 59.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1924, the Ku Klux Klan Colorado Realm achieved dominance in Colorado politics.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] With peak membership levels, the Second Klan levied significant control over both the local and state Democrat and Republican parties, particularly in the governor's office and city governments of Denver, Cañon City, and Durango.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] A particularly strong element of the Klan controlled the Denver Police.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Cross burnings became semi-regular occurrences in cities such as Florence and Pueblo.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Klan targeted African-Americans, Catholics, Eastern European immigrants, and other non-White Protestant groups.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Efforts by non-Klan lawmen and lawyers including Philip Van Cise led to a rapid decline in the organization's power, with membership waning significantly by the end of the 1920s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado became the first western state to host a major political convention when the Democratic Party met in Denver in 1908.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] By the U.S. census in 1930, the population of Colorado first exceeded one million residents.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado suffered greatly through the Great Depression and the Dust Bowl of the 1930s, but a major wave of immigration following World War II boosted Colorado's fortune.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Tourism became a mainstay of the state economy, and high technology became an important economic engine.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The United States Census Bureau estimated that the population of Colorado exceeded five million in 2009.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On September 11, 1957, a plutonium fire occurred at the Rocky Flats Plant, which resulted in the significant plutonium contamination of surrounding populated areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] From the 1940s and 1970s, many protest movements gained momentum in Colorado, predominantly in Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] This included the Chicano Movement, a civil rights, and social movement of Mexican Americans emphasizing a Chicano identity that is widely considered to have begun in Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The National Chicano Youth Liberation Conference was held in Colorado in March 1969.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1967, Colorado was the first state to loosen restrictions on abortion when governor John Love signed a law allowing abortions in cases of rape, incest, or threats to the woman's mental or physical health.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Many states followed Colorado's lead in loosening abortion laws in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Since the late 1990s, Colorado has been the site of multiple major mass shootings, including the Columbine High School massacre in 1999, where high school senior students Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 13 students and one teacher, before committing suicide.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The incident made international news, and has since spawned many copycat incidents, known as the Columbine effect.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On July 20, 2012, a gunman killed 12 people in a movie theater in Aurora.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The state responded with tighter restrictions on firearms, including introducing a limit on magazine capacity.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On March 22, 2021, a gunman killed 10 people, including a police officer, in a King Soopers supermarket in Boulder.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In an instance of anti-LGBT violence, a gunman killed 5 people at a nightclub in Colorado Springs during the night of November 19–20, 2022.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Navy have been named the USS *Colorado*.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The first USS *Colorado* was named for the Colorado River and served in the Civil War and later the Asiatic Squadron, where it was attacked during the 1871 Korean Expedition.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The later three ships were named in honor of the state, including an armored cruiser and the battleship USS *Colorado*, the latter of which was the lead ship of her class and served in World War II in the Pacific beginning in 1941.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] At the time of the attack on Pearl Harbor, the battleship USS *Colorado* was located at the naval base in San Diego, California, and thus went unscathed.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The most recent vessel to bear the name USS *Colorado* is Virginia-class submarine USS *Colorado* (SSN-788), which was commissioned in 2018.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado is notable for its diverse geography, which includes alpine mountains, high plains, deserts with huge sand dunes, and deep canyons.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 1861, the United States Congress defined the boundaries of the new Territory of Colorado exclusively by lines of latitude and longitude, stretching from 37°N to 41°N latitude, and from 102°02′48″W to 109°02′48″W longitude (25°W to 32°W from the Washington Meridian).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] After 165 years of government surveys, the borders of Colorado were officially defined by 697 boundary markers and 697 straight boundary lines.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado, Wyoming, and Utah are the only states that have their borders defined solely by straight boundary lines with no natural features.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The southwest corner of Colorado is the Four Corners Monument at 36°59′56″N, 109°2′43″W.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument, located at the place where Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah meet, is the only place in the United States where four states meet.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Approximately half of Colorado is flat and rolling land.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] East of the Rocky Mountains is the Colorado Eastern Plains of the High Plains, the section of the Great Plains within Colorado at elevations ranging from roughly 3,350 to 7,500 feet (1,020 to 2,290 m).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado plains are mostly prairies but also include deciduous forests, buttes, and canyons.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Precipitation averages 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado is presently mainly farmland and rangeland, along with small farming villages and towns.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Corn, wheat, hay, soybeans, and oats are all typical crops.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Most villages and towns in this region boast both a water tower and a grain elevator.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Irrigation water is available from both surface and subterranean sources.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Surface water sources include the South Platte, the Arkansas River, and a few other streams.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Subterranean water is generally accessed through artesian wells.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Heavy usage of these wells for irrigation purposes caused underground water reserves to decline in the region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Eastern Colorado also hosts a considerable amount and range of livestock, such as cattle ranches and hog farms.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] About 84% of Colorado's population resides along the eastern edge of the Rocky Mountains in the Front Range Urban Corridor between Cheyenne, Wyoming, and Pueblo, Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] This region is partially protected from prevailing storms that blow in from the Pacific Ocean region by the high Rockies in the middle of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The "Front Range" includes Denver, Boulder, Fort Collins, Loveland, Castle Rock, Colorado Springs, Pueblo, Greeley, and other townships and municipalities in between.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On the other side of the Rockies, the significant population centers in western Colorado (which is known as "The Western Slope") are the cities of Grand Junction, Durango, and Montrose.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] To the west of the Great Plains of Colorado rises the eastern slope of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Notable peaks of the Rocky Mountains include Longs Peak, Mount Blue Sky, Pikes Peak, and the Spanish Peaks near Walsenburg, in southern Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] This area drains to the east and the southeast, ultimately either via the Mississippi River or the Rio Grande into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Rocky Mountains within Colorado contain 53 true peaks and 58 named peaks that are 14,000 feet (4,267 m) or higher in elevation above sea level, known as fourteeners.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] These mountains are largely covered with trees such as conifers and aspens up to the tree line, at an elevation of about 12,000 feet (3,658 m) in southern Colorado to about 10,500 feet (3,200 m) in northern Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Above this tree line, only alpine vegetation grows.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Much of the alpine snow melts by mid-August except for a few snow-capped peaks and a few small glaciers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado Mineral Belt, stretching from the San Juan Mountains in the southwest to Boulder and Central City on the front range, contains most of the historic gold- and silver-mining districts of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The 30 highest major summits of the Rocky Mountains of North America are all within the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The summit of Mount Elbert at 14,437.6 feet (4,400.58 m) elevation in Lake County is the highest point in Colorado and the Rocky Mountains of North America.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Colorado is the only U.S. state that lies entirely above 1,000 meters elevation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The point where the Arikaree River flows out of Yuma County, Colorado, and into Cheyenne County, Kansas, is the lowest in Colorado at 3,317 feet (1,011 m) elevation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] This point, which is the highest low elevation point of any state, is higher than the high elevation points of 18 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Continental Divide of the Americas extends along the most of the crest of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The area of Colorado to the west of the Continental Divide is called the Western Slope of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] West of the Continental Divide, water flows to the southwest via the Colorado River and the Green River towards the Gulf of California.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Within the interior of the Rocky Mountains are several large parks which are high broad basins.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In the north, on the east side of the Continental Divide is the North Park of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The North Park is drained by the North Platte River, which flows north into Wyoming and Nebraska.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Just to the south of North Park, but on the western side of the Continental Divide, is the Middle Park of Colorado, which is drained by the Colorado River.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The South Park of Colorado is the region of the headwaters of the South Platte River.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In south-central Colorado is the large San Luis Valley, where the headwaters of the Rio Grande are located.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The northern part of the valley is the San Luis Closed Basin, an endorheic basin that helped created the Great Sand Dunes.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The valley sits between the Sangre de Cristo Mountains and San Juan Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Rio Grande drains due south into New Mexico, Texas, and Mexico.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Across the Sangre de Cristo Range to the east of the San Luis Valley lies the Wet Mountain Valley.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] These basins, particularly the San Luis Valley, lie along the Rio Grande rift, a major geological formation of the Rocky Mountains, and its branches.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado includes the western face of the Rocky Mountains and all of the area to the western border.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] This area includes several terrains and climates from alpine mountains to arid deserts.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes many ski resort towns in the Rocky Mountains and towns west to Utah.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] It is less populous than the Front Range but includes a large number of national parks and monuments.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The northwestern corner of Colorado is a sparsely populated region, and it contains part of the noted Dinosaur National Monument, which not only is a paleontological area, but is also a scenic area of rocky hills, canyons, arid desert, and streambeds.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Here, the Green River briefly crosses over into Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope of Colorado is drained by the Colorado River and its tributaries (primarily the Gunnison River, Green River, and the San Juan River).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Colorado River flows through Glenwood Canyon, and then through an arid valley made up of desert from Rifle to Parachute, through the desert canyon of De Beque Canyon, and into the arid desert of Grand Valley, where the city of Grand Junction is located.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Also prominent is the Grand Mesa, which lies to the southeast of Grand Junction; the high San Juan Mountains, a rugged mountain range; and to the north and west of the San Juan Mountains, the Colorado Plateau.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction, Colorado, at the confluence of the Colorado and Gunnison Rivers, is the largest city on the Western Slope.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction and Durango are the only major centers of television broadcasting west of the Continental Divide in Colorado, though most mountain resort communities publish daily newspapers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is located at the juncture of Interstate 70 and US 50, the only major highways in western Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Grand Junction is also along the major railroad of the Western Slope, the Union Pacific.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] This railroad also provides the tracks for Amtrak's *California Zephyr* passenger train, which crosses the Rocky Mountains between Denver and Grand Junction.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Western Slope includes multiple notable destinations in the Colorado Rocky Mountains, including Glenwood Springs, with its resort hot springs, and the ski resorts of Aspen, Breckenridge, Vail, Crested Butte, Steamboat Springs, and Telluride.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Higher education in western and southwestern Colorado includes Colorado Mesa University in Grand Junction, Western Colorado University in Gunnison, Fort Lewis College in Durango, and Colorado Mountain College campuses in Glenwood Springs and Steamboat Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Four Corners Monument in the southwest corner of Colorado marks the common boundary of Colorado, New Mexico, Arizona, and Utah, the only such place in the United States.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The climate of Colorado is more complex than states outside of the Mountain States region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Unlike most other states, southern Colorado is not always warmer than northern Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Most of Colorado is made up of mountains, foothills, high plains, and desert lands.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Mountains and surrounding valleys greatly affect the local climate.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Northeast, east, and southeast Colorado are mostly the high plains, while Northern Colorado is a mix of high plains, foothills, and mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Northwest and west Colorado are predominantly mountainous, with some desert lands mixed in.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Southwest and southern Colorado are a complex mixture of desert and mountain areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The climate of the Eastern Plains is semi-arid (Köppen climate classification: *BSk*) with low humidity and moderate precipitation, usually from 15 to 25 inches (380 to 640 mm) annually, although many areas near the rivers are semi-humid climate.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The area is known for its abundant sunshine and cool, clear nights, which give this area a great average diurnal temperature range.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The difference between the highs of the days and the lows of the nights can be considerable as warmth dissipates to space during clear nights, the heat radiation not being trapped by clouds.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Front Range urban corridor, where most of the population of Colorado resides, lies in a pronounced precipitation shadow as a result of being on the lee side of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In summer, this area can have many days above 95 °F (35 °C) and often 100 °F (38 °C).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On the plains, the winter lows usually range from 25 to −10 °F (−4 to −23 °C).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] About 75% of the precipitation falls within the growing season, from April to September, but this area is very prone to droughts.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Most of the precipitation comes from thunderstorms, which can be severe, and from major snowstorms that occur in the winter and early spring.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Otherwise, winters tend to be mostly dry and cold.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In much of the region, March is the snowiest month.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] April and May are normally the rainiest months, while April is the wettest month overall.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Front Range cities closer to the mountains tend to be warmer in the winter due to Chinook winds which warm the area, sometimes bringing temperatures of 70 °F (21 °C) or higher in the winter.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The average July temperature is 55 °F (13 °C) in the morning and 90 °F (32 °C) in the afternoon.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The average January temperature is 18 °F (−8 °C) in the morning and 48 °F (9 °C) in the afternoon, although variation between consecutive days can be 40 °F (4 °C).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Just west of the plains and into the foothills, there is a wide variety of climate types.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Locations merely a few miles apart can experience entirely different weather depending on the topography.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Most valleys have a semi-arid climate, not unlike the eastern plains, which transitions to an alpine climate at the highest elevations.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Microclimates also exist in local areas that run nearly the entire spectrum of climates, including subtropical highland (*Cfb/Cwb*), humid subtropical (*Cfa*), humid continental (*Dfa/Dfb*), Mediterranean (*Csa/Csb*) and subarctic (*Dfc*).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Extreme weather changes are common in Colorado, although a significant portion of the extreme weather occurs in the least populated areas of the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Thunderstorms are common east of the Continental Divide in the spring and summer, yet are usually brief.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Hail is a common sight in the mountains east of the Divide and across the eastern Plains, especially the northeast part of the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Hail is the most commonly reported warm-season severe weather hazard, and occasionally causes human injuries, as well as significant property damage.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The eastern Plains are subject to some of the biggest hail storms in North America.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Notable examples are the severe hailstorms that hit Denver on July 11, 1990, and May 8, 2017, the latter being the costliest ever in the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Eastern Plains are part of the extreme western portion of Tornado Alley; some damaging tornadoes in the Eastern Plains include the 1990 Limon F3 tornado and the 2008 Windsor EF3 tornado, which devastated a small town.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Portions of the eastern Plains see especially frequent tornadoes, both those spawned from mesocyclones in supercell thunderstorms and from less intense landspouts, such as within the Denver convergence vorticity zone (DCVZ).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The Plains are also susceptible to occasional floods and particularly severe flash floods, which are caused both by thunderstorms and by the rapid melting of snow in the mountains during warm weather.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Notable examples include the 1965 Denver Flood, the Big Thompson River flooding of 1976 and the 2013 Colorado floods.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Hot weather is common during summers in Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The city's record in 1901 for the number of consecutive days above 90 °F (32 °C) was broken during the summer of 2008.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The new record of 24 consecutive days surpassed the previous record by almost a week.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Much of Colorado is very dry, with the state averaging only 17 inches (430 mm) of precipitation per year statewide.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The state rarely experiences a time when some portion is not in some degree of drought.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The lack of precipitation contributes to the severity of wildfires in the state, such as the Hayman Fire of 2002.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Other notable fires include the Fourmile Canyon Fire of 2010, the Waldo Canyon Fire and High Park Fire of June 2012, and the Black Forest Fire of June 2013.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Even these fires were exceeded in severity by the Pine Gulch Fire, Cameron Peak Fire, and East Troublesome Fire in 2020, all being the three largest fires in Colorado history (see 2020 Colorado wildfires).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] And the Marshall Fire which started on December 30, 2021, while not the largest in state history, was the most destructive ever in terms of property loss (see Marshall Fire).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] However, some of the mountainous regions of Colorado receive a huge amount of moisture from winter snowfalls.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The spring melts of these snows often cause great waterflows in the Yampa River, the Colorado River, the Rio Grande, the Arkansas River, the North Platte River, and the South Platte River.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Water flowing out of the Colorado Rocky Mountains is a very significant source of water for the farms, towns, and cities of the southwest states of New Mexico, Arizona, Utah, and Nevada, as well as the Midwest, such as Nebraska and Kansas, and the southern states of Oklahoma and Texas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] A significant amount of water is also diverted for use in California; occasionally (formerly naturally and consistently), the flow of water reaches northern Mexico.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Climate change in Colorado encompasses the effects of climate change, attributed to man-made increases in atmospheric greenhouse gases, in the U.S. state of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 2019 *The Denver Post* reported that "[i]ndividuals living in southeastern Colorado are more vulnerable to potential health effects from climate change than residents in other parts of the state".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Most of the state has warmed one or two degrees (F) in the last century.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Throughout the western United States, heat waves are becoming more common, snow is melting earlier in spring, and less water flows through the Colorado River.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Rising temperatures and recent droughts in the region have killed many trees by drying out soils, increasing the risk of forest fires, or enabling outbreaks of forest insects.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In the coming decades, the changing climate is likely to decrease water availability and agricultural yields in Colorado, and further increase the risk of wildfires".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The highest official ambient air temperature ever recorded in Colorado was 115 °F (46.1 °C) on July 20, 2019, at John Martin Dam.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The lowest official air temperature was −61 °F (−51.7 °C) on February 1, 1985, at Maybell.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Despite its mountainous terrain, Colorado experiences less seismic activity than states like California and Alaska.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] There are over 90 potentially active faults, and since 1867, Colorado has experienced 700 recorded earthquakes of magnitude 2.5 or higher.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] National Earthquake Information Center is located in Golden.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] On August 22, 2011, a 5.3 magnitude earthquake occurred 9 miles (14 km) west-southwest of the city of Trinidad.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] There were no casualties and only a small amount of damage was reported.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] It was the second-largest earthquake in Colorado's history, the largest being a magnitude 6.6 earthquake, recorded in 1882.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Four minor earthquakes rattled Colorado on August 24, 2018, ranging from magnitude 2.9 to 4.3.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] As of June 2020, there were 525 recorded earthquakes in Colorado since 1973, a majority of which range 2 to 3.5 on the Richter scale.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] A process of extirpation by trapping and poisoning of the gray wolf (*Canis lupus*) from Colorado in the 1930s saw the last wild wolf in the state shot in 1945.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] A wolf pack recolonized Moffat County, Colorado in northwestern Colorado in 2019.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Cattle farmers have expressed concern that a returning wolf population potentially threatens their herds.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Coloradans voted to reintroduce gray wolves in 2020, with the state committing to a plan to have a population in the state by 2022 and permitting non-lethal methods of driving off wolves attacking livestock and pets.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Despite being an artificially-introduced species, the state declared mountain goats a native species in 1993.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] In 2013, 2014, and 2019, an unknown illness killed nearly all mountain goat kids, leading to a Colorado Parks and Wildlife investigation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The native population of pronghorn in Colorado has varied wildly over the last century, reaching a low of only 15,000 individuals during the 1960s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] However, conservation efforts succeeded in bringing the stable population back up to roughly 66,000 by 2013.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The population was estimated to have reached 85,000 by 2019 and had increasingly more run-ins with the increased suburban housing along the eastern Front Range.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] State wildlife officials suggested that landowners would need to modify fencing to allow the greater number of pronghorns to move unabated through the newly developed land.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Pronghorns are most readily found in the northern and eastern portions of the state, with some populations also in the western San Juan Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] Common wildlife found in the mountains of Colorado include mule deer, southwestern red squirrel, golden-mantled ground squirrel, yellow-bellied marmot, moose, American pika, and red fox, all at exceptionally high numbers, though moose are not native to the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The foothills include deer, fox squirrel, desert cottontail, mountain cottontail, and coyote.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p01] The prairies are home to black-tailed prairie dog, the endangered swift fox, American badger, and white-tailed jackrabbit.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Like the federal government and all other U.S. states, Colorado's state constitution provides for three branches of government: the legislative, the executive, and the judicial branches.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Governor of Colorado heads the state's executive branch.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The current governor is Jared Polis, a Democrat.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's other statewide elected executive officers are the Lieutenant Governor of Colorado (elected on a ticket with the Governor), Secretary of State of Colorado, Colorado State Treasurer, and Attorney General of Colorado, all of whom serve four-year terms.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The seven-member Colorado Supreme Court is the state's highest court.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Colorado Court of Appeals, with 22 judges, sits in divisions of three judges each.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is divided into 23 judicial districts, each of which has a district court and a county court with limited jurisdiction.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state also has specialized water courts, which sit in seven distinct divisions around the state and which decide matters relating to water rights and the use and administration of water.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state legislative body is the Colorado General Assembly, which is made up of two houses – the House of Representatives and the Senate.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The House has 65 members and the Senate has 35.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] As of April 2026, the Democratic Party holds a 23 to 12 majority in the Senate and a 43 to 22 majority in the House.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] State sales taxes and many state-collected local sales taxes are administered and collected by the Colorado Department of Revenue.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado was once considered a swing state, but has become a relatively safe blue state in both state and federal elections since the late 2010s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In presidential elections, it had not been won until 2020 by double digits since 1984 and has backed the winning candidate in 9 of the last 11 elections.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Coloradans have elected 17 Democrats and 12 Republicans to the governorship in the last 100 years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In presidential politics, Colorado was considered a reliably Republican state during the post-World War II era, voting for the Democratic candidate only in 1948, 1964, and 1992.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] However, it became a competitive swing state in the 1990s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Since the mid-2000s, it has swung heavily to the Democrats, voting for Barack Obama in 2008 and 2012, Hillary Clinton in 2016, Joe Biden in 2020, and Kamala Harris in 2024.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado politics exhibits a contrast between conservative cities such as Colorado Springs and Grand Junction, and liberal cities such as Boulder and Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Democrats are strongest in metropolitan Denver, the college towns of Fort Collins and Boulder, southern Colorado (including Pueblo), and several western ski resort counties.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Republicans are strongest in the Eastern Plains, Colorado Springs, Greeley, and far Western Colorado near Grand Junction.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In a 2020 study, Colorado was ranked as the seventh easiest state for citizens to vote in.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado was the first state in the union to enact, by voter referendum, a law extending suffrage to women.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] That initiative was approved by the state's voters on November 7, 1893.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On the November 8, 1932, ballot, Colorado approved the repeal of alcohol prohibition more than a year before the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution was ratified.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has banned, via C.R.S. section 12-6-302, the sale of motor vehicles on Sunday since at least 1953.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 1972, Colorado voters rejected a referendum proposal to fund the 1976 Winter Olympics, which had been scheduled to be held in the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver had been chosen by the International Olympic Committee as the host city on May 12, 1970.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Supreme Court found that preventing protected status based upon homosexuality or bisexuality did not satisfy the Equal Protection Clause.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2006, voters passed Amendment 43, which banned same-sex marriage in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] That initiative was nullified by the U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Supreme Court's 2015 decision in *Obergefell v.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2024, Colorado residents voted to establish an explicit right to abortion in Colorado's state constitution and to repeal Amendment 43's defunct marriage ban.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2012, voters amended the state constitution protecting the "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate cannabis like alcohol.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The first recreational marijuana shops in Colorado, and by extension the United States, opened their doors on January 1, 2014.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On October 30, 2019, Colorado became the first state to accept digital ID via its myColorado app.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state-issued digital identifications will be considered valid when Real ID enforcement begins in 2025, in line with the Real ID Act of 2005.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] By November 2022 The Colorado Governor's Office of Information Technology announced that the myColorado app had over 1 million users.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On December 19, 2023, the Colorado Supreme Court ruled that Donald Trump was disqualified from the 2024 United States presidential election in part due to his alleged incitement of the January 6 United States Capitol attack.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On March 4, 2024, the United States Supreme Court overruled the Colorado decision.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The State of Colorado is divided into 64 counties.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Two of these counties, the City and County of Broomfield and the City and County of Denver, have consolidated city and county governments.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Counties are important units of government in Colorado since there are no civil townships or other minor civil divisions.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous county in Colorado is El Paso County, the home of the City of Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The second most populous county is the City and County of Denver, the state capital.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Five of the 64 counties now have more than 500,000 residents, while 12 have fewer than 5,000 residents.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The ten most populous Colorado counties are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Mesa County is the most populous county on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The least populous Colorado county is Hinsdale County with 747 residents.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has 273 active incorporated municipalities, comprising 198 towns, 73 cities, and two consolidated city and county governments.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] At the 2020 United States census, 4,299,942 of the 5,773,714 Colorado residents (74.47%) lived in one of these municipalities.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Another 714,417 residents (12.37%) lived in one of the 210 census-designated places, while the remaining 759,355 residents (13.15%) lived in the many rural and mountainous areas of the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado municipalities operate under one of five types of municipal governing authority.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado currently has two consolidated city and county governments, 61 home rule cities, 12 statutory cities, 35 home rule towns, 161 statutory towns, and one territorial charter municipality.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous municipality is the City and County of Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has 12 municipalities with more than 100,000 residents, and 17 with fewer than 100 residents.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The 16 most populous Colorado municipalities are all located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The City of Grand Junction is the most populous municipality on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Town of Carbonate has had no year-round population since the 1890 census due to its severe winter weather and difficult access.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In addition to its 272 municipalities, Colorado has 210 unincorporated census-designated places (CDPs) and many other small communities.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous unincorporated community in Colorado is Highlands Ranch south of Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The seven most populous CDPs are located in the Front Range Urban Corridor.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Clifton CDP is the most populous CDP on the Colorado Western Slope.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has more than 4,000 special districts, most with property tax authority.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] These districts may provide health services, ambulance, schools, law enforcement, fire protection, water, sewage, drainage, irrigation, transportation, recreation, infrastructure, cultural facilities, business support, redevelopment, or other services.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Some of these districts have the authority to levy sales tax as well as property tax and use fees.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The 17 core-based statistical areas in the U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Most recently on July 21, 2023, the Office of Management and Budget defined 21 statistical areas for Colorado comprising four combined statistical areas, seven metropolitan statistical areas, and ten micropolitan statistical areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous of the seven metropolitan statistical areas in Colorado is the 10-county Denver–Aurora–Centennial, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area with a population of 2,963,821 at the 2020 United States census, an increase of +15.29% since the 2010 census.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The more extensive 12-county Denver–Aurora–Greeley, CO Combined Statistical Area had a population of 3,623,560 at the 2020 census, an increase of +17.23% since the 2010 census.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The most populous extended metropolitan region in Rocky Mountain Region is the 18-county Front Range Urban Corridor along the northeast face of the Southern Rocky Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] This region with Denver at its center had a population of 5,055,344 at the 2020 census, an increase of +16.65% since the 2010 census.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The United States Census Bureau estimated the population of Colorado on July 1, 2024, at 5,957,493, a 3.2% increase since the 2020 United States census.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Coloradan Hispanics and Latinos (of any race and heritage) made up 20.7% of the population.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] According to the 2000 census, the largest ancestry groups in Colorado are German (22%), Mexican (18%), Irish (12%), and English (12%).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Persons reporting German ancestry are especially numerous in the Front Range, the Rockies (west-central counties), and Eastern parts/High Plains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has a high proportion of Hispanic, mostly Mexican-American, citizens in Metropolitan Denver, Colorado Springs, as well as the smaller cities of Greeley and Pueblo, and elsewhere.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Southern, Southwestern, and Southeastern Colorado have a large number of Hispanos, the descendants of the early settlers of colonial Spanish origin.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Census Bureau reported Colorado's population as 8.2% Hispanic and 90.3% non-Hispanic White.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Hispanic population of Colorado has continued to grow quickly over the past decades.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] By 2019, Hispanics made up 22% of Colorado's population, and Non-Hispanic Whites made up 70%.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Spoken English in Colorado has many Spanish idioms.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado also has some large African-American communities located in Denver, in the neighborhoods of Montbello, Five Points, Whittier, and many other East Denver areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In the 2020 Census, 234,828 Colorado residents were identified as African American (of the total 5,773,714).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Arapahoe, at 10.8% African American, was the only one of the state's 64 counties where African Americans make up more than 10% of the population.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] African Americans in the seven counties of Arapahoe (70,787), Denver (64,038), El Paso (43,822), Adams (17,463), Jefferson (7,356), Douglas (5,160), and Weld (4,539) make up more than 90% of all African Americans in the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The population of Native Americans in the state is small.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Native Americans are concentrated in metropolitan Denver and the southwestern corner of Colorado, where there are two Ute reservations.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The majority of Colorado's immigrants are from Mexico, India, China, Vietnam, Korea, Germany and Canada.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] There were a total of 70,331 births in Colorado in 2006.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] (Birth rate of 14.6 per thousand.) In 2007, non-Hispanic Whites were involved in 59.1% of all births.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Some 14.06% of those births involved a non-Hispanic White person and someone of a different race, most often with a couple including one Hispanic.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] A birth where at least one Hispanic person was involved counted for 43% of the births in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Per the 2000 census, the Hispanic population is estimated to be 918,899, or approximately 20% of the state's total population.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has the 5th-largest population of Mexican-Americans, behind California, Texas, Arizona, and Illinois.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In percentages, Colorado has the 6th-highest percentage of Mexican-Americans, behind New Mexico, California, Texas, Arizona, and Nevada.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2011, 46% of Colorado's population younger than the age of one were minorities, meaning that they had at least one parent who was not non-Hispanic White.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2017, Colorado recorded the second-lowest fertility rate in the United States outside of New England, after Oregon, at 1.63 children per woman.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Significant contributing factors to the decline in pregnancies were the Title X Family Planning Program and an intrauterine device grant from Warren Buffett's family.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] English, the official language of the state, is the most commonly spoken language in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The second most commonly spoken language in the state is Spanish.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Colorado River Numic language, also known as the Ute dialect, is still spoken in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Major religious affiliations of the people of Colorado as of 2014 were 64% Christian, of whom there are 44% Protestant, 16% Roman Catholic, 3% Mormon, and 1% Eastern Orthodox.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Other religious breakdowns according to the Pew Research Center were 1% Judaism, 1% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, and 4% other.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Secular Coloradans made up 29% of the population.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2020, according to the Public Religion Research Institute, Christianity was 66% of the population.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Judaism was also reported to have increased in this separate study, forming 2% of the religious landscape, while the religiously unaffiliated were reported to form 28% of the population in this separate study.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2022, the same organization reported 61% was Christian (39% Protestant, 19% Catholic, 2% Mormon, 1% Eastern Orthodox), 2% New Age, 1% Jewish, 1% Hindu, and 34% religiously unaffiliated.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] According to the Association of Religion Data Archives, the largest Christian denominations by the number of adherents in 2010 were the Catholic Church with 811,630; multi-denominational Evangelical Protestants with 229,981; and the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 151,433.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2020, the Association of Religion Data Archives determined the largest Christian denominations were Catholics (873,236), non/multi/inter-denominational Protestants (406,798), and Mormons (150,509).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Throughout its non-Christian population, there were 12,500 Hindus, 7,101 Hindu Yogis, and 17,369 Buddhists at the 2020 study.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Our Lady of Guadalupe Catholic Church was the first permanent Catholic parish in modern-day Colorado and was constructed by Spanish colonists from New Mexico in modern-day Conejos.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Latin Church Catholics are served by three dioceses: the Archdiocese of Denver and the Dioceses of Colorado Springs and Pueblo.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The first permanent settlement by members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Colorado arrived from Mississippi and initially camped along the Arkansas River just east of the present-day site of Pueblo.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is generally considered among the healthiest states by behavioral and healthcare researchers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Among the positive contributing factors is the state's well-known outdoor recreation opportunities and initiatives.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] However, there is a stratification of health metrics with wealthier counties such as Douglas and Pitkin performing significantly better relative to southern, less wealthy counties such as Huerfano and Las Animas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] According to several studies, Coloradans have the lowest rates of obesity of any state in the US.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] As of 2018, 24% of the population was considered medically obese, and while the lowest in the nation, the percentage had increased from 17% in 2004.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] According to a report in the *Journal of the American Medical Association*, residents of Colorado had a 2014 life expectancy of 80.21 years, the longest of any U.S. state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 10,397 homeless people in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The number of employer establishments is 174,258.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's gross domestic product in 2025 was $584.3 billion.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's per capita personal income was $86,181 in 2025, ranking Colorado 10th in the nation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Median Annual Household Income in 2016 was $70,666, 8th in the nation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's economy broadened from its mid-19th-century roots in mining when irrigated agriculture developed, and by the late 19th century, raising livestock had become important.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Early industry was based on the extraction and processing of minerals and agricultural products.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Current agricultural products are cattle, wheat, dairy products, corn, and hay.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2025, small businesses made up 99.5% of Colorado businesses, and employed 48.6% of the state's work force.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Geological Survey and other government agencies at the Denver Federal Center near Lakewood; the Denver Mint, Buckley Space Force Base, the Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals, and the Byron G.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Rogers Federal Building and United States Courthouse in Denver; and a federal Supermax Prison and other federal prisons near Cañon City.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In addition to these and other federal agencies, Colorado has abundant National Forest land and four National Parks that contribute to federal ownership of 24,615,788 acres (99,617 km2) of land in Colorado, or 37% of the total area of the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In the second half of the 20th century, the industrial and service sectors expanded greatly.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's economy is diversified and is notable for its concentration on scientific research and high-technology industries.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Other industries include food processing, transportation equipment, machinery, chemical products, the extraction of metals such as gold (see Gold mining in Colorado), silver, and molybdenum.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado now also has the largest annual production of beer in any state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver is an important financial center.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's diverse geography and majestic mountains attract millions of tourists every year, including 85.2 million in 2018.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Tourism contributes greatly to Colorado's economy, with tourists generating $22.3 billion in 2018.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Several nationally known brand names have originated in Colorado factories and laboratories.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] From Denver came the forerunner of telecommunications giant Qwest in 1879, Samsonite luggage in 1910, Gates belts and hoses in 1911, and Russell Stover Candies in 1923.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Kuner canned vegetables began in Brighton in 1864.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] From Golden came Coors beer in 1873, CoorsTek industrial ceramics in 1920, and Jolly Rancher candy in 1949.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] CF&I railroad rails, wire, nails, and pipe debuted in Pueblo in 1892.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Holly Sugar was first milled from beets in Holly in 1905, and later moved its headquarters to Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The present-day Swift packed meat of Greeley evolved from Monfort of Colorado, Inc., established in 1930.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Estes model rockets were launched in Penrose in 1958.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Fort Collins has been the home of Woodward Governor Company's motor controllers (governors) since 1870, and Waterpik dental water jets and showerheads since 1962.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Celestial Seasonings herbal teas have been made in Boulder since 1969.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Rocky Mountain Chocolate Factory made its first candy in Durango in 1981.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has a flat 4.63% income tax, regardless of income level.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On November 3, 2020, voters authorized an initiative to lower that income tax rate to 4.55 percent.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Unlike most states, which calculate taxes based on federal *adjusted gross income*, Colorado taxes are based on *taxable income*—income after federal exemptions and federal itemized (or standard) deductions.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's state sales tax is 2.9% on retail sales.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] When state revenues exceed state constitutional limits, according to Colorado's Taxpayer Bill of Rights legislation, full-year Colorado residents can claim a sales tax refund on their individual state income tax return.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Many counties and cities charge their own rates, in addition to the base state rate.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] There are also certain county and special district taxes that may apply.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Real estate and personal business property are taxable in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state's senior property tax exemption was temporarily suspended by the Colorado Legislature in 2003.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The tax break was scheduled to return for the assessment year 2006, payable in 2007.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] As of May 2025, the state's unemployment rate was 4.8%.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The West Virginia teachers' strike in 2018 inspired teachers in other states, including Colorado, to take similar action.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Corn is grown in the Eastern Plains of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Arid conditions and drought negatively impacted yields in 2020 and 2022.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado has significant hydrocarbon resources.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] According to the Energy Information Administration, Colorado hosts seven of the largest natural gas fields in the United States, and two of the largest oil fields.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Conventional and unconventional natural gas output from several Colorado basins typically accounts for more than five percent of annual U.S. natural gas production.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's oil shale deposits hold an estimated 1 trillion barrels (160 km3) of oil—nearly as much oil as the entire world's proven oil reserves.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Substantial deposits of bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite coal are found in the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Uranium mining in Colorado goes back to 1872, when pitchblende ore was taken from gold mines near Central City, Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Not counting byproduct uranium from phosphate, Colorado is considered to have the third-largest uranium reserves of any U.S. state, behind Wyoming and New Mexico.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] When Colorado and Utah dominated radium mining from 1910 to 1922, uranium and vanadium were the byproducts (giving towns like present-day Superfund site Uravan their names).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Uranium price increases from 2001 to 2007 prompted several companies to revive uranium mining in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] During the 1940s certain communities–including Naturita and Paradox–earned the moniker of "yellowcake towns" from their relationship with uranium mining.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Price drops and financing problems in late 2008 forced these companies to cancel or scale back the uranium-mining project.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] As of 2016, there were no major uranium mining operations in the state, though plans existed to restart production.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's high Rocky Mountain ridges and eastern plains offer wind power potential, and geologic activity in the mountain areas provides the potential for geothermal power development.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Much of the state is sunny and could produce solar power.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Major rivers flowing from the Rocky Mountains offer hydroelectric power resources.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Several film productions have been shot on location in Colorado, especially prominent Westerns like *True Grit*, *The Searchers*, *City Slickers,* *Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid, and My Life With the Walter Boys*.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Several historic military forts, railways with trains still operating, and mining ghost towns have been used and transformed for historical accuracy in well-known films.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] There are also several scenic highways and mountain passes that helped to feature the open road in films such as *Vanishing Point*, *Bingo* and *Starman*.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Some Colorado landmarks have been featured in films, such as The Stanley Hotel in *Dumb and Dumber* and *The Shining* and the Sculptured House in *Sleeper*.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2015, *Furious 7* was to film driving sequences on Pikes Peak Highway in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The TV adult-animated series *South Park* takes place in central Colorado in the titular town.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Additionally, the TV series *Good Luck Charlie* was set, but not filmed, in Denver, Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Colorado Office of Film and Television has noted that more than 400 films have been shot in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On March 27, 2025, it was announced Sundance Film Festival would move to Boulder starting in 2027 after reaching a deal for a ten-year duration.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Many notable writers have lived or spent extended periods in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] *5280*, a Denver magazine, wrote in 2015 that Kent Haruf is "widely considered [to be] Colorado's finest novelist"; Haruf set his novels in the fictional high plains Colorado town of Holt.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Beat Generation writers Jack Kerouac and Neal Cassady lived in and around Denver for several years each.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Irish playwright Oscar Wilde visited Colorado on his tour of the United States in 1882, writing in his 1906 *Impressions of America* that Leadville was "the richest city in the world.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is known for its Southwest and Rocky Mountain cuisine, with Mexican restaurants found throughout the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Boulder was named America's Foodiest Town 2010 by Bon Appétit.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Boulder, and Colorado in general, is home to several national food and beverage companies, top-tier restaurants and farmers' markets.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Boulder also has more Master Sommeliers per capita than any other city, including San Francisco and New York.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver is known for steak, but now has a diverse culinary scene with many restaurants.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Polidori Sausage is a brand of pork products available in supermarkets, which originated in Colorado, in the early 20th century.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Food & Wine Classic is held annually each June in Aspen.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Aspen also has a reputation as the culinary capital of the Rocky Mountain region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado wines include varietals that have attracted favorable notice from outside the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] With wines made from traditional *Vitis vinifera* grapes along with wines made from cherries, peaches, plums, and honey, Colorado wines have won top national and international awards for their quality.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's grape growing regions contain the highest elevation vineyards in the United States, with most viticulture in the state practiced between 4,000 and 7,000 feet (1,219 and 2,134 m) above sea level.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The mountain climate ensures warm summer days and cool nights.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to two designated American Viticultural Areas of the Grand Valley AVA and the West Elks AVA, where most of the vineyards in the state are located.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] However, an increasing number of wineries are located along the Front Range.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 2018, Wine Enthusiast Magazine named Colorado's Grand Valley AVA in Mesa County, Colorado, as one of the Top Ten wine travel destinations in the world.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is home to many nationally praised microbreweries, including New Belgium Brewing Company, Odell Brewing Company, and Great Divide Brewing Company.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The area of northern Colorado near and between the cities of Denver, Boulder, and Fort Collins is known as the "Napa Valley of Beer" due to its high density of craft breweries.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado is open to cannabis (marijuana) tourism.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] With the adoption of the 64th state amendment in 2012, Colorado became the first state in the union to legalize marijuana for medicinal (2000), industrial (referring to hemp, 2012), and recreational (2012) use.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's marijuana industry sold $1.31 billion worth of marijuana in 2016 and $1.26 billion in the first three-quarters of 2017.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state generated tax, fee, and license revenue of $194 million in 2016 on legal marijuana sales.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado regulates hemp as any part of the plant with less than 0.3% THC.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On April 4, 2014, Senate Bill 14–184 addressing oversight of Colorado's industrial hemp program was first introduced, ultimately being signed into law by Governor John Hickenlooper on May 31, 2014.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On November 7, 2000, 54% of Colorado voters passed Amendment 20, which amends the Colorado State constitution to allow the medical use of marijuana.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Currently, Colorado has listed "eight medical conditions for which patients can use marijuana—cancer, glaucoma, HIV/AIDS, muscle spasms, seizures, severe pain, severe nausea and cachexia, or dramatic weight loss and muscle atrophy".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] While governor, John Hickenlooper allocated about half of the state's $13 million "Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund" to medical research in the 2014 budget.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] By 2018, the Medical Marijuana Program Cash Fund was the "largest pool of pot money in the state" and was used to fund programs including research into pediatric applications for controlling autism symptoms.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On November 6, 2012, voters amended the state constitution to protect "personal use" of marijuana for adults, establishing a framework to regulate marijuana in a manner similar to alcohol.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's primary mode of transportation (in terms of passengers) is its highway system.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Interstate 25 (I-25) is the primary north–south highway in the state, connecting Pueblo, Colorado Springs, Denver, and Fort Collins, and extending north to Wyoming and south to New Mexico.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] It connects Grand Junction and the mountain communities with Denver and enters Utah and Kansas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The state is home to a network of US and Colorado highways that provide access to all principal areas of the state.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Many smaller communities are connected to this network only via county roads.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Denver International Airport (DIA) is the third-busiest domestic U.S. and international airport in the world by passenger traffic.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] DIA handles by far the largest volume of commercial air traffic in Colorado and is the busiest U.S. hub airport between Chicago and the Pacific coast, making Denver the most important airport for connecting passenger traffic in the western United States.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Public transportation bus services are offered both intra-city and inter-city—including the Denver metro area's RTD services.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Regional Transportation District (RTD) operates the popular RTD Bus & Rail transit system in the Denver Metropolitan Area.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] As of January 2013 the RTD rail system had 170 light-rail vehicles, serving 47 miles (76 km) of track.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In addition to local public transit, intercity bus service is provided by Burlington Trailways, Bustang and Greyhound Lines.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Amtrak operates two passenger rail lines in Colorado, the *California Zephyr* and *Southwest Chief*.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's contribution to world railroad history was forged principally by the Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad which began in 1870 and wrote the book on mountain railroading.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 1988 the "Rio Grande" was acquired, but was merged into, the Southern Pacific Railroad by their joint owner Philip Anschutz.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On September 11, 1996, Anschutz sold the combined company to the Union Pacific Railroad, creating the largest railroad network in the United States.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The Anschutz sale was partly in response to the earlier merger of Burlington Northern and Santa Fe which formed the large Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway (BNSF), Union Pacific's principal competitor in western U.S. railroading.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Both Union Pacific and BNSF have extensive freight operations in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Colorado's freight railroad network consists of 2,688 miles of Class I trackage.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] It is integral to the U.S. economy, being a critical artery for the movement of energy, agriculture, mining, and industrial commodities as well as general freight and manufactured products between the East and Midwest and the Pacific coast states.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In August 2014, Colorado began to issue driver licenses to aliens not lawfully in the United States who lived in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In September 2014, KCNC reported that 524 non-citizens were issued Colorado driver licenses that are normally issued to U.S. citizens living in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The first institution of higher education in the Colorado Territory was the Colorado Seminary, opened on November 16, 1864, by the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The seminary closed in 1867 but reopened in 1880 as the University of Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] In 1870, the Bishop George Maxwell Randall of the Episcopal Church's Missionary District of Colorado and Parts Adjacent opened the first of what become the Colorado University Schools which would include the Territorial School of Mines opened in 1873 and sold to the Colorado Territory in 1874.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] These schools were initially run by the Episcopal Church.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] An 1861 territorial act called for the creation of a public university in Boulder, though it would not be until 1876 that the University of Colorado was founded.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The 1876 act also renamed Territorial School of Mines as the Colorado School of Mines.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] An 1870 territorial act created the Agricultural College of Colorado which opened in 1879.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The college was renamed the Colorado State College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts in 1935, and became Colorado State University in 1957.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The first Catholic college in Colorado was the Jesuit Sacred Heart College, which was founded in New Mexico in 1877, moved to Morrison in 1884, and to Denver in 1887.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The college was renamed Regis College in 1921 and Regis University in 1991.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1924, armed students patrolled the campus after a burning cross was found, the climax of tensions between Regis College and the locally-powerful Ku Klux Klan.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Following a 1950 assessment by the Service Academy Board, it was determined that there was a need to supplement the U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Military and Naval Academies with a third school that would provide commissioned officers for the newly independent Air Force.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] On April 1, 1954, President Dwight Eisenhower signed a law that moved for the creation of a U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] Later that year, Colorado Springs was selected to host the new institution.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] From its establishment in 1955, until the construction of appropriate facilities in Colorado Springs was completed and opened in 1958, the Air Force Academy operated out of Lowry Air Force Base in Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] With the opening of the Colorado Springs facility, the cadets moved to the new campus, though not in the full-kit march that some urban and campus legends suggest.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The first class of Space Force officers from the Air Force Academy commissioned on April 18, 2020.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The two Native American reservations remaining in Colorado are the Southern Ute Indian Reservation (1873; Ute dialect: *Kapuuta-wa Moghwachi Núuchi-u*) and Ute Mountain Ute Indian Reservation (1940; Ute dialect: *Wʉgama Núuchi*).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p02] The two abolished Indian reservations in Colorado were the Cheyenne and Arapaho Indian Reservation (1851–1870) and Ute Indian Reservation (1855–1873).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p03] Colorado has five major professional sports leagues, all based in the Denver metropolitan area.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p03] Colorado is the least populous state with a franchise in each of the major professional sports leagues.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p03] The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb is a major hill climbing motor race held on the Pikes Peak Highway.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p03] The Cherry Hills Country Club has hosted several professional golf tournaments, including the U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p03] Women's Open, PGA Championship and BMW Championship.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-p03] The following universities and colleges participate in the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division I.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] At 6,035 feet (1,839 m), the city stands over 1 mile (1.6 km) above sea level.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It is near the base of Pikes Peak, which rises 14,115 feet (4,302.31 m) above sea level on the eastern edge of the Southern Rocky Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Ute, Arapaho and Cheyenne peoples were the first recorded inhabiting the area which would become Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Part of the territory included in the United States' 1803 Louisiana Purchase, the current city area was designated part of the 1854 Kansas Territory.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 1859, after the first local settlement was established, it became part of the Jefferson Territory on October 24 and of El Paso County on November 28.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado City at the Front Range confluence of Fountain and Camp creeks was "formally organized on August 13, 1859" during the Pikes Peak Gold Rush.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Colorado City, Kansas Territory, post office operated from March 24, 1860, until it closed as the Colorado City, Colorado, post office on June 30, 1917.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado City served as the capital of the Colorado Territory from November 5, 1861, until August 14, 1862, when the capital was moved to Golden.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 1871 the Colorado Springs Company laid out the towns of La Font (later called Manitou Springs) and **Fountain Colony**, upstream and downstream respectively, of Colorado City.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Later that year, the Fountain Colony was renamed Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Colorado Springs, Colorado Territory, post office opened on December 1, 1871.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The El Paso County seat shifted from Colorado City in 1873 to the Town of Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] So many immigrants from England had settled in Colorado Springs by the early 1870s that Colorado Springs was locally referred to as "Little London".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The town of Colorado Springs was incorporated on June 19, 1886.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A second period of annexations occurred during 1889–90, which included Seavey's Addition, West Colorado Springs, East End, and another North End addition.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] From 1899 to 1901 Tesla Experimental Station operated on Knob Hill, and aircraft flights to the Broadmoor's neighboring fields began in 1919.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Alexander Airport north of the city opened in 1925, and in 1927 the original Colorado Springs Municipal Airport land was purchased east of the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The city's military presence began during World War II, beginning with Camp Carson (now the 135,000-acre Fort Carson base) that was established in 1941.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] During the war, the United States Army Air Forces leased land adjacent to the municipal airfield, naming it Peterson Field in December 1942.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In November 1950, Ent Air Force Base was selected as the Cold War headquarters for Air Defense Command (ADC).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The former WWII Army Air Base, Peterson Field, which had been inactivated at the end of the war, was re-opened in 1951 as a U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] North American Aerospace Defense Command (NORAD) was established as a hardened command and control center within the Cheyenne Mountain Complex during the Cold War.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Between 1965 and 1968, the University of Colorado Colorado Springs, Pikes Peak State College and Colorado Technical University were established in or near the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 1977 most of the former Ent AFB became a US Olympic training center.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Libertarian Party was founded within the city in the 1970s.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] On October 1, 1981, the Broadmoor Addition, Cheyenne Canon, Ivywild, Skyway, and Stratton Meadows were annexed after the Colorado Supreme Court "overturned a district court decision that voided the annexation".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Further annexations expanding the city include the Nielson Addition and Vineyard Commerce Park Annexation in September 2008.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] On June 23, 2012, the Waldo Canyon fire began 4 miles (6.4 km) northwest of the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The fire ended up destroying 347 homes and killing two people in the city, causing the evacuation of 32,000 residents.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] At the time the fire was the most destructive in state history until it was surpassed by the Black Forest Fire the following year.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The city lies in a semi-arid Steppe region, with the Southern Rocky Mountains to the west, the Palmer Divide to the north, high plains further east, and high desert lands to the south when leaving Fountain and approaching Pueblo.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs is 69 miles (111 km) or at best one hour and five minutes south of Denver by car using I-25.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs has the greatest total area of any municipality in Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] During the 2020 United States census, the city had a total area of 195.761 square miles (507.019 km2) including 0.362 square miles (0.937 km2) of water.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The city has abundant sunshine year-round, averaging 243 sunny days per year, and receives approximately 16.5 inches (419 mm) of annual precipitation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Due to unusually low precipitation for several years after flooding in 1999, Colorado Springs enacted lawn water restrictions in 2002.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] These were lifted in 2005 but permanently reinstated in December 2019.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs is one of the most active lightning strike areas in the United States.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] This natural phenomenon led Nikola Tesla to select Colorado Springs as the preferred location to build his lab and study electricity.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] December is typically the coldest month, averaging 30.8 °F (−0.7 °C).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Historically, January had been the coldest month, but, in recent years, December has had both lower daily maxima and minima.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Typically, there are 5.2 nights with sub-0 °F (−18 °C) lows and 23.6 days where the high does not rise above freezing.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In addition, 8 of the top 10 heaviest 24-hour snowfalls have occurred from March to May.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Summers are warm, with July, the warmest month, averaging 70.9 °F (21.6 °C), and 18 days of 90 °F (32 °C)+ highs annually.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Due to the high elevation and aridity, nights are usually relatively cool and rarely does the low remain above 70 °F (21 °C).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Dry weather generally prevails, but brief afternoon thunderstorms are common, especially in July and August when the city receives the majority of its annual rainfall, due to the North American monsoon.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The first autumn freeze and the last freeze in the spring, on average, occur on October 2 and May 6, respectively; the average window for measurable snowfall (≥0.1 in or 0.25 cm) is October 21 through April 25.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Mexican Americans made up 14.6% of the city's population, compared with 9.1% in 1990.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The median age in the city was 35 years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs's economy is driven primarily by the military, the high-tech industry, and tourism, in that order.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The city is experiencing slight growth in the service sectors.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] As of April 2025, the unemployment rate in Colorado Springs was 4.6%.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The state's unemployment rate was 4.8% compared to 4.2% for the nation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] As of 2021, there are nearly 45,000 active-duty troops in the Colorado Springs area.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] There are more than 100,000 veterans and thousands of reservists.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The military and defense contractors supply more than 40% of the Pikes Peak region's economy.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs is home to the Peterson Space Force Base, Schriever Space Force Base, Cheyenne Mountain Space Force Station, U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Space Command, and Space Operations Command—the largest contingent of space service military installations, responsible for intelligence gathering, space operations, and cyber missions.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Peterson Space Force Base is responsible for the North American Aerospace Defense Command (NORAD) and the United States Northern Command (USNORTHCOM) headquarters, Space Operations Command, and Space Deltas 2, 3, and 7.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Located at Peterson is the 302nd Airlift Wing, an Air Force Reserve unit, that transports passengers and cargo and fights wildfires.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Schriever Space Force Base is responsible for Joint Task Force-Space Defense and Space Deltas 6, 8, and 9.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The NORAD and USNORTHCOM Alternate Command Center is located at the Cheyenne Mountain Complex.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Within the mountain complex, the Cheyenne Mountain Space Force Station has been operated by Space Operations Command.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] On January 13, 2021, the Air Force announced a new permanent home for Space Command, moving it from Colorado Springs to Huntsville, Alabama in 2026, but the decision could be reversed by Congress.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Army divisions are trained and stationed at Fort Carson.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The United States Air Force Academy was established after World War II on land donated by the City of Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The defense industry forms a significant part of the Colorado Springs economy, with some of the city's largest employers being defense contractors.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Some defense corporations have left or downsized city campuses, but slight growth has been recorded.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Significant defense corporations in the city include Northrop Grumman, Boeing, General Dynamics, L3Harris Technologies, SAIC, ITT, Lockheed Martin, and Bluestaq.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Space Foundation is based in Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A large percentage of Colorado Springs's economy is still based on manufacturing high-tech and complex electronic equipment.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The high-tech sector in the Colorado Springs area has decreased its overall presence from 2000 to 2006 (from around 21,000 to around 8,000), with notable reductions in information technology and complex electronic equipment.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Current trends project the high-tech employment ratio will continue to decrease.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] High-tech corporations offering fibre-optics to the premises connections within the city include: Lumen Technologies, Comcast and other providers as of 2023.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Hewlett-Packard still has some sales, support, and SAN storage engineering center for the computer industry.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Storage Networking Industry Association is the home of the SNIA Technology Center.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Keysight Technologies, spun off in 2014 from Agilent, which was itself spun off from HP in 1999 as an independent, publicly traded company, has its oscilloscope research and development division based in Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Intel had 250 employees in 2009 but has ceased operations.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Intel facility is now used for the centralized unemployment offices, social services, El Paso county offices, and a bitcoin mining facility.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Microchip Technology (formerly Atmel), is a chip fabrication organization.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Apple Inc. facility was sold to Sanmina-SCI in 1996.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Almost immediately following the arrival of railroads beginning in 1871, the city's location at the base of Pikes Peak and the Rocky Mountains made it a popular tourism destination.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Tourism is the third largest employer in the Pikes Peak region, accounting for more than 16,000 jobs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2018, 23 million day and overnight visitors came to the area, contributing $2.4 billion in revenue.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2020, the United States Olympic & Paralympic Museum opened; the Flying W Ranch Chuckwagon Dinner & Western Show reopened in 2020.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A new Pikes Peak Summit Complex opened at the 14,115-foot (4,302 m) summit in 2021.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Manitou and Pikes Peak Railway also reopened in 2021.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The downtown Colorado Springs Visitor Information Center offers free area information to leisure and business travelers.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Cultural Office of the Pikes Peak Region (COPPeR), also downtown, supports and advocates for the arts throughout the Pikes Peak Region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It operates the PeakRadar website to communicate city events.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs is home to the annual Colorado Springs Labor Day Lift Off, a hot air balloon festival that takes place over Labor Day weekend at the city's Memorial Park.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Colorado Springs Festival of Lights Parade is held the first Saturday in December.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The parade is held on Tejon Street in Downtown Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2017, Colorado had the third-most craft breweries at 348 in the United States.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Breweries and microbreweries have become popular in Colorado Springs, which hosts over 30 of them.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Although houses of worship of almost every major world religion are within the city, Colorado Springs has in particular attracted a large influx of Evangelical Christians and Christian organizations in recent years.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] At one time Colorado Springs was the national headquarters for 81 different religious organizations, earning the city the tongue-in-cheek nicknames "the Evangelical Vatican" and "The Christian Mecca".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Although Colorado voters approved Colorado Amendment 64, a constitutional amendment in 2012 legalizing retail sales of marijuana for recreational purposes, the Colorado Springs city council voted not to permit retail shops in the city, as was allowed in the amendment.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Medical marijuana outlets continue to operate in Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2015, there were 91 medical marijuana clinics in the city, which reported sales of $59.6 million in 2014, up 11 percent from the previous year but without recreational marijuana shops.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] On April 26, 2016, Colorado Springs city council decided to extend the current six-month moratorium to eighteen months with no new licenses to be granted until May 2017.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A scholarly paper suggested the city would give up $25.4 million in tax revenue and fees if the city continued to thwart the industry from opening within the city limits.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] As of March 1, 2018, there were 131 medical marijuana centers and no recreational cannabis stores.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In November 2024 a referendum vote allowed existing medical marijuana dispensaries to obtain recreational marijuana sales licenses, and recreational sales began in April 2025.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs has been the subject of or setting for many books, films and television shows, and is a frequent backdrop for political thrillers and military-themed stories because of its many military installations and vital importance to the United States' continental defense.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Notable television series using the city as a setting include *Dr.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Quinn, Medicine Woman*, *Homicide Hunter* and the *Stargate* series *Stargate SG-1*, as well as the films *WarGames*, *The Prestige*, and *BlacKkKlansman*.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In a North Korean propaganda video released in April 2013, Colorado Springs was singled out as one of four targets for a missile strike.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The video failed to pinpoint Colorado Springs on the map, instead showing a spot somewhere in Louisiana.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs, dubbed Olympic City USA, is home to the United States Olympic & Paralympic Training Center and the headquarters of the United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee and the United States Anti-Doping Agency.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Further, over 50 national sports organizations (non-Olympic) headquarter in Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] These include the National Strength and Conditioning Association, Sports Incubator, a various non-Olympic Sports (such as USA Ultimate), and more.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs and Denver hosted the 1962 World Ice Hockey Championships.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The city has a long association with the sport of figure skating, having hosted the U.S.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Figure Skating Championships six times and the World Figure Skating Championships five times.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It is home to the World Figure Skating Museum and Hall of Fame and the Broadmoor Skating Club, a notable training center for the sport.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In recent years, the Broadmoor World Arena has hosted skating events such as Skate America and the Four Continents Figure Skating Championships.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs was home to a professional baseball team, the Rocky Mountain Vibes, who are a member of the Pioneer League, an MLB Partner League.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Vibes no longer play in Colorado Springs as of 2026.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The United States Hang Gliding and Paragliding Association (USHPA) is based out of Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb (PPIHC), also known as *The Race to the Clouds,* is an annual invitational automobile and motorcycle hill climb to the summit of Pikes Peak, every year on the last Sunday of June.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The highway was not completely paved until 2011.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The local colleges feature many sports teams.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Notable among them are several nationally competitive NCAA Division I teams: United States Air Force Academy (Falcons) Football, Basketball and Hockey and Colorado College (Tigers) Hockey, and Women's Soccer.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs was the original headquarters of the Professional Bull Riders (PBR) from its founding in 1992 until 2005, when the organization was moved to Pueblo.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The city's Parks, Recreation and Cultural Services manage 136 neighborhood parks, eight community parks, seven regional parks, and five sports complexes, totaling 9,000 acres (3,600 ha).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] They also manage 500 acres (200 ha) of trails, of which 160 miles (260 km) are park trails and 105 miles (169 km) are urban.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] There are 5,000 acres (2,000 ha) of open space in 48 open-space areas.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Garden of the Gods is on Colorado Springs's western edge.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It is a National Natural Landmark, with 300 foot (91 m) red/orange sandstone rock formations often viewed against a backdrop of the snow-capped Pikes Peak.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] This park is free to the public and offers many recreational opportunities, such as hiking, rock climbing, cycling, horseback riding and tours.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It offers a variety of annual events, one of the most popular of which is the Starlight Spectacular, a recreational bike ride held every summer to benefit the Trails and Open Space Coalition of Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Monument Valley Park also has Tahama Spring, the original spring in Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Austin Bluffs Park affords a place of recreation in eastern Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] El Paso County Regional Parks include Bear Creek Regional Park, Bear Creek Dog Park, Fox Run Regional Park and Fountain Creek Regional Park and Nature Center.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Ponderosa pine (*Pinus ponderosa*), Gambel oak (*Quercus gambelii*), narrowleaf yucca (*Yucca angustissima*, syn.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] *Yucca glauca*) and prickly pear cactus (*Opuntia macrorhiza*).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Three trails, the New Santa Fe Regional Trail, Pikes Peak Greenway and Fountain Creek Regional Trail, form a continuous path from Palmer Lake, through Colorado Springs, to Fountain, Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The majority of the trail between Palmer Lake and Fountain is a soft surface breeze gravel trail.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A major segment of the trail within the Colorado Springs city limits is paved.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The trails, except Monument Valley Park trails, may be used for equestrian traffic.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Motorized vehicles are not allowed on the trails.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Many of the trails are interconnected, having main spine trails, like the Pikes Peak Greenway, that lead to secondary trails.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] On November 2, 2010, Colorado Springs voters adopted a council-strong mayor form of government.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The City of Colorado Springs transitioned to the new system of government in 2011.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Under the council-strong mayor system of government, the mayor is the chief executive and the city council is the legislative branch.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The mayor is a full-time elected position and not a member of the council.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The council has nine members, six of whom represent one of six equally populated districts each.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The remaining three members are elected at-large.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs City Hall was built from 1902 to 1904 on land donated by W.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Colorado Springs City Council is the legislative branch that governs the City of Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It has 3 members elected by the district at-large, with a combined total of 9 official members elected at-large, with a total 6 of the elected officials representing equally-populated quadrants.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The current City Council president, Lynnette Crow-Iverson, was sworn in on April 14, 2025.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2017, Caleb Hannan wrote in *Politico* that Colorado Springs was "staunchly Republican", "a right-wing counterweight to liberal Boulder", and that a study ranked it "the fourth most conservative city in America".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2016, Hannan wrote that downtown Colorado Springs had a different political vibe from the overall area's and that there were "superficial signs of changing demographics".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] However, since 2020, Colorado Springs has continued to shift towards the political center.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2022, Governor Jared Polis won the city in his bid for reelection.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In the 2023 mayoral election, independent candidate Yemi Mobolade handily won the race and became the first elected non-Republican mayor of the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In addition the state of Colorado runs the Colorado School for the Deaf and Blind, a residential school for people up to age 21 and established in 1874, in the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] State institutions offering bachelors and graduate degree programs in Colorado Springs include the University of Colorado Colorado Springs (UCCS) with more than 12,000 students and Pikes Peak State College which offers mostly two-year degree associate degrees.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The United States Air Force Academy is a federal institution offering bachelor's degrees for officer candidates.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Private non-profit institutions include Colorado College established in 1874 with about 2,000 undergraduates.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Christian University has its Colorado Springs Center in the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Private for-profit institutions include Colorado Technical University whose main campus is in Colorado Springs and IntelliTec College a technical training school.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] I-25 runs north and south through Colorado, and traverses the city for nearly 18 miles (29 km), entering the city south of Academy Blvd and exiting north of North Gate Boulevard.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In El Paso County it is known as Ronald Reagan Highway.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] An Interstate 25 bypass was approved in 2010.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A number of state and U.S. highways serve the city.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] State Highway 21 is a major east side semi-expressway from Black Forest to Fountain, known locally and co-signed as Powers Boulevard.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] State Highway 83 runs north–south from central Denver to northern Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] State Highway 94 runs east–west from western Cheyenne County to eastern Colorado Springs where it terminates at US 24.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] US 24 is a major route through the city and county, providing access to Woodland Park via Ute Pass to the west and downtown, Nob Hill and numerous suburbs to the east.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It is co-signed with Platte Ave after SH 21 and originally carried local traffic through town.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Martin Luther King Jr Bypass runs from I-25 near Circle Drive along Fountain Blvd to SH 21, then east again.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] State Highway 115 begins in Cañon City, traveling north along the western edge of Fort Carson; when it reaches the city limits it merges with Nevada Avenue, a signed Business Route of US 85.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] US 85 and SH 115 are concurrent between Lake Avenue and I-25.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] US 85 enters the city at Fountain and was signed at Venetucci Blvd, Lake Avenue, and Nevada Avenue at various points in history; however most of US 85 is concurrent with I-25 and is not signed.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2004, the voters of Colorado Springs and El Paso County established the Pikes Peak Rural Transportation Authority.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs Airport (COS; ICAO: KCOS) has been in operation since 1925.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It is the second-largest commercial airport in the state, after Denver International Airport (DEN; ICAO: KDEN).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] It covers 7,200 acres (2,900 ha) of land at an elevation of approximately 6,200 feet (1,900 m).
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] COS is considered to be a joint-use civilian and military airport, as Peterson Space Force Base is a tenant of the airport.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The airport handled 2,134,618 passengers in 2022, and is served by American, Avelo, Delta, Southwest, Sun Country, and United.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Freight service is provided by Union Pacific and BNSF.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Once an important hub, the city was once served by four Class 1 railroads, as well as a number of smaller operators, some of which were narrow gauge, and an extensive streetcar system, the Colorado Springs and Interurban Railway.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Currently there is no intercity passenger service; the last remaining services connecting the Front Range cities ceased with the formation of Amtrak in 1971.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Front Range Passenger Rail is a current proposal (as of 2023) to link the cities from Pueblo in the south, north to Fort Collins and possibly Cheyenne, Wyoming.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] As of 2017, Colorado Springs has 121 miles (195 km) of bike lanes and 82 miles (132 km) of paved trails.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] PikeRide is a local electric bike-share program that operates in urban core, Old Colorado City, and Manitou Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In April 2018, the Colorado Springs City Council approved a Bike Master Plan.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Bike lanes in Colorado Springs have not been deployed without controversy.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] According to *The Gazette*, their readers "have mixed feelings for new bike lanes." In December 2016, the City removed a bike lane along Research Parkway due to overwhelming opposition; an online survey found that 80.5% of respondents opposed the bike lane.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] *The Gazette* has stated that since the Bike Master Plan was adopted by city council, "no issue has elicited more argument in *The Gazette* pages," and due to this immense public interest, on February 25, 2019, *The Gazette* hosted a town hall meeting called "Battle of the Bike Lanes".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A 2011 study by Walk Score ranked Colorado Springs 34th most walkable of fifty largest U.S. cities.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Mountain Metropolitan Transit (commonly referred to as MMT) is the primary public transportation provider for the Colorado Springs metropolitan region.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] MMT operates thirty-four bus routes, providing service for Colorado Springs, Manitou Springs, and Security-Widefield.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Downtown Terminal is the system's main hub, with the Citadel Mall, PPSC, and Chapel Hills Mall acting as secondary transfer stations.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Mountain Metro Mobility is an Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) federally mandated complementary ADA paratransit service, which provides demand-response service for individuals with mobility needs that prevent them from using the fixed-route bus system.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Intercity bus service is available through the state-ran Bustang service and Greyhound.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Bustang runs frequent trips to Denver, and daily trips to Lamar via Pueblo.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] Colorado Springs's sister city organization began when it became partners with Fujiyoshida.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The *torii* gate erected to commemorate the relationship stands at the corner of Bijou Street and Nevada Avenue, and is one of the city's most recognizable landmarks.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The *torii* gate, crisscrossed bridge and shrine, in the median between Platte and Bijou Streets downtown, were a gift to Colorado Springs, erected in 1966 by the Rotary Club of Colorado Springs to celebrate the friendship between the two communities.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A plaque near the *torii* gate states that "the purpose of the sister city relationship is to promote understanding between the people of our two countries and cities".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] The Fujiyoshida Student exchange program has become an annual event.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] In 2006 and 2010, the Bankstown TAP (Talent Advancement Program) performed with the Youth Symphony and the Colorado Springs Children's Chorale as part of the annual "In Harmony" program.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-springs] A notable similarity between Colorado Springs and its sister cities is their geographic positions: three of the seven cities are near the foot of a major mountain or mountain range, as is Colorado Springs.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The **Colorado State Capitol Building**, located at 200 East Colfax Avenue in Denver, Colorado, United States, is the home of the Colorado General Assembly and the offices of the Governor of Colorado, Lieutenant Governor of Colorado, and the Colorado State Treasurer.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The building is intentionally reminiscent of the United States Capitol.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Myers, it was constructed in the 1890s from Colorado white granite, and opened for use in November 1894.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The distinctive gold dome consists of real gold leaf, first added in 1908, commemorating the Colorado Gold Rush.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The building is part of Denver's Civic Center area.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places as part of the Civic Center Historic District in 1974, and became part of the Denver Civic Center National Historic Landmark District in 2012.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] A major safety upgrade project, funded by the Colorado State Historical Fund, was started in 2001 and completed in 2009.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The design by Fentress Architects added modern safety features, like enclosed stair towers, that blended in with the original architecture.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The Colorado Capitol Building is featured on many of Denver's architectural tours.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Serving as the beginning of the Capitol Hill district, the historic building sits slightly higher than the rest of downtown Denver.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The main entrance hall is open 180 feet (55 m) to the top of the dome, about the height of an 18-story building.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Additionally, the official elevation of Denver is measured outside the west entrance to the building, where the fifteenth step is engraved with the words "One Mile Above Sea Level".
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] From this step, at 5,280 feet (1,609 m), the sun can be seen setting behind the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] A second mile high marker was set in the 18th step in 1969 when Colorado State University students resurveyed the elevation.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] In 2003, a more accurate measurement was made with modern means, and the 13th step was identified as being one mile (1.6 km) high, where a 3rd marker was installed.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The superstructure of the building was constructed using granite from the Aberdeen Quarry near Gunnison, Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Approximately 280,000 cubic feet (7,900 m3) or 24,000 tons of the granite were quarried for the building.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] This gray granite forms the exterior of the building.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The interior of the building uses a large amount of Colorado Rose Onyx, a rare rose marble from a quarry near Beulah, Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The amount used in the building consumed the entire known supply.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] White Yule Marble from the quarries near Marble, Colorado was also used throughout the capitol for the floors.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Many designs have been found in the marble including an image resembling George Washington and another of Molly Brown.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Many of the windows are made of stained glass, depicting people or events related to the history of Colorado.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] The halls are decorated with portraits of every president of the United States, with all the presidents from George Washington to George W.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Bush being painted by Lawrence Williams.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Boardman took over from Williams, and has since painted Barack Obama and the original portrait of Donald Trump, which was removed after Trump criticized it and replaced with one by Arizonan artist Vanessa Horabuena.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Colorado artist Kirsten Savage painted President Joe Biden's portrait.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] One of the contractors for the construction of the Colorado State Capitol building was Illinois building contractor William Douglas Richardson, who was the president of the W.
[src:1881-colorado-state-capital-referendum/colorado-state-capitol] Richardson had participated in numerous major building contracts throughout the United States, and was interconnected with the Jacob Bunn and John Whitfield Bunn network of corporations.
